(42, 2, '2011-07-28 14:20:32', '2011-07-28 14:20:32', '<p>Meet the Families That Can team and find out more about how we work with charter school parents to make sure your voice is heard!</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/zzgCIzLRwKE" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><a href="http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLC7F71762C4202382">See more videos from Families That Can, including Charter Schools 101 and a message from our Executive Director.</a></p>\n', 'Check out our new video!', 'Meet the Families That Can team and find out more about how we work with charter school parents to make sure your voice is heard!\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'check_out_our_new_video', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/check_out_our_new_video/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(43, 2, '2011-08-17 11:52:05', '2011-08-17 11:52:05', '<p><a href="/corri_ravare.jpg"><img alt="Corri Ravare" src="/assets_c/2011/08/corri_ravare-thumb-210x315-1957.jpg" width="210" height="315" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></a> I am a proud South Los Angeles native.   My parents were teenage parents, who did not get the opportunity to go to college, but they wanted me and my sister to go to college so they sent us to college-preparatory Catholic schools from kindergarten through high school. My parents took extra work and sacrificed a great deal to give us the education they believed we deserved.\nThat\'s one of the things that charter schools changes for a lot of families like mine - you can have choices and options without having to overextend the families\' resources to give your kids opportunity.\nWith the support of my parents, I went to college at UC Berkeley, where I was surrounded by students and faculty who felt compelled to make a difference in their community.  I learned how to take action to solve community problems - how you organize people, get out your message and get access to the people who could make the change happen.  I participated in my fair share of rallies, sit-ins and protests!\nIt was through my student job that I started to focus on the need for change in our public schools. I coordinated a team of tutors who worked with students in Oakland and Berkeley to get them up to grade level and to prepare them for the state standardized tests. It was a really great experience to be involved with kids and families who were a lot like me and be able to help them in a real way.\nI moved back to Los Angeles after I graduated and the push for education reform was really picking up momentum.  I ended up working for the Los Angeles Unified School District\'s reform initiative, LEARN, and for LAUSD board member Genethia Hudley-Hayes, who was elected on a reform ticket.  The community became energized during Genethia\'s time on the board because she pushed the South Los Angeles community to do for ourselves what needed to be done to make change.\nThe first charter schools were starting to open and I had the chance to visit many of them and see first-hand the wonderful work that was taking place - the way parents were involved and the sense of community. I found out about a charter school that had just been opened by the Inner-City Educational Foundation (ICEF) in South Los Angeles and that already had thousands of kids on their waiting list. That was how excited parents were to have a school like this in our community. Both of my kids attended ICEF schools and a major part of the success of the school was that all of the parents were really involved and committed.\nWhile at ICEF, we heard that the state legislature was looking at cutting millions of dollars of facilities funding for charter schools. I joined with other charter schools in Los Angeles to form Families That Can and 700 parents marched and spoke out.  We were successful. Parents really do have power!  I\'m honored to continue working with parents to give them the tools and support to have their voices heard.</p>\n', 'Meet Corri Ravare', 'Meet Corri Ravare, a charter school parent, former charter school leader and now the Executive Director of Families That Can\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'meet_corri_ravare', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/meet_corri_ravare/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(44, 2, '2011-10-25 16:54:19', '2011-10-25 16:54:19', '<p>KIPP Bridge in Oakland was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. It was also honored as Charter School of the Year in 2010. <a href="http://youtu.be/hGmelk57y-o">See a video about the report</a>.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/iYarUaJdvis" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Are you a parent or student at KIPP Bridge? We want to hear from you! Why did you choose to go to a charter school? What do you like about your school? Send your story to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a>.</p>\n', 'Eye on Success: KIPP Bridge in Oakland', 'KIPP Bridge in Oakland was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. Find out more about this great school!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'kipp_bridge_in_oakland', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '2016-01-13 04:14:43', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/kipp_bridge_in_oakland/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(45, 2, '2011-10-26 09:14:12', '2011-10-26 09:14:12', '<p>Watts Learning Center, an elementary charter school in South Los Angeles, was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. It was also honored as Charter School of the Year in 2007. <a href="http://youtu.be/hGmelk57y-o">See a video about the report</a>.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="410" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/C-awbRJN3to" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Are you a parent or student at Watts Learning Center? We want to hear from you! Why did you choose to go to a charter school? What do you like about your school? Send your story to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a>.</p>\n', 'Eye on Success: Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles', 'Watts Learning Center, an elementary charter school in South Los Angeles, was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'watts_learning_center_in_los_angeles', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/watts_learning_center_in_los_angeles/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(46, 2, '2011-10-26 09:17:36', '2011-10-26 09:17:36', '<p>Charter school parent Marie Cole shared her story and perspective at a press conference in September on how charter schools are effectively serving African American students. She is a parent at at PS7 in Sacramento.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/M8lKHaieb2c" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><em>See Marie at minute 27 of the press conference.</em>\nMy oldest son is a senior at Sac High this year. He was in the first fourth-grade class of PS7 when Mayor Kevin Johnson first founded the school. I found the school on a fluke. It was in the summertime and there were yard signs out that said "Charter school opening - enroll your student." I went and met the administrators and signed up. Two weeks later, I got a letter that my son had been accepted.\nI had been lead to believe that my son had a learning disability because, in the second and third grade, he would finish his work more quickly than the other kids, then he would get distracted and he would distract his classmates. His teachers didn\'t have time to give him extra work. We went to PS7 and my son excelled - he was an overachiever and it was a blessing. It wasn\'t something that was frowned upon. It wasn\'t punished - he was encouraged more and more to excel.\nIt made me look at not only wanting to help the school, but to be more a part of his education. At many traditional public schools, you\'re not really allowed to just walk in and say, "Hi, can I help?" They will say, "No, we have a PTA for that." But not here at PS7 - it\'s an open door policy. They want you to come in and be here and volunteer. I kind of became a fixture at the school, which was a blessing. This school is very family-oriented. To see these scores, it\'s awesome. As a parent, it\'s exciting because my son is a part of this.\nFind out more about the African American student report and schools in Oakland and Los Angeles that were also highlighted for being highly effective.</p>\n', 'Marie Cole, PS7 in Sacramento', '"This school is very family-oriented. To see these test scores, it\'s awesome. As a parent, it\'s exciting because my son is a part of this. "\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'marie_cole_ps7_in_sacramento', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/marie_cole_ps7_in_sacramento/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(47, 2, '2011-10-26 09:33:09', '2011-10-26 09:33:09', '<p>St. HOPE Public School 7 (PS7) is a K-8 charter school located in Sacramento. It was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. <a href="http://youtu.be/hGmelk57y-o">See a video about the report</a>.\n"If you are a parent in Sacramento county, charter schools are your northern star," said Margaret Fortune, founder of Fortune Schools. "If you are a parent that is making the decision, it is your choice. It is about your children and following what is best for them, even if it takes courage."\n"We believe that black and Latino kids have to have an opportunity to succeed and achieve the American dream. If you look at the achievement gap in Sacramento, there is an 151 point gap between black kids and white kids. Over the last eight years, that gap has closed five points. At that rate, it will take 258 years to close the achievement gap. I don\'t know about you, but I\'m not waiting that long," said Sacramento Mayor Kevin Johnson, one of the founders of PS7.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/15531078?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0" width="559" height="317" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><a href="http://vimeo.com/15531078">PS7 Featured On KCRA</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/user4883473">PS7</a> on <a href="http://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.ps7.org/">Learn more about PS7</a>.</li>\n<li>Hear a parent\'s perspective: <a href="/2011/10/marie-cole-ps7-in-sacramento.html">Marie Cole, PS7</a>\nAre you a parent or student at PS7? We want to hear from you! Why did you choose to go to PS7? What do you like about your school? Send your story to (contact@familiesthatcan.org)[contact@familiesthatcan.org].</li>\n</ul>\n', 'St. HOPE Public School 7 in Sacramento', 'St. HOPE Public School 7 (PS7) is a K-8 charter school located in Sacramento. It was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'st_hope_public_school_7_in_sacramento', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/st_hope_public_school_7_in_sacramento/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(48, 2, '2011-10-26 09:37:31', '2011-10-26 09:37:31', '<p>A new report issued by the California Charter Schools Association found that charter schools are accelerating the achievement of African American students.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/hGmelk57y-o" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>"What this report shows is that African American students are experiencing better outcomes in charters, and that as laboratories of innovation, California\'s highly effective charter public schools can demonstrate proven paths to success that should be replicated nationally," said Dr. Aisha Toney, Director of Research, CCSA.\nAmong the report\'s findings:</p>\n\n<h3>African American parents are choosing charter schools in high numbers.</h3>\n\n<p>African American students make up 6% of students statewide, but 9% of students in charter public schools. In some communities, African Americans are twice as likely to enroll in a charter than a traditional public school.</p>\n\n<h3>Charter schools are helping to close the achievement gap.</h3>\n\n<p>Charter schools serving African American students are realizing better outcomes compared to traditional public schools. While charters make up only 9% of schools statewide, they represent 39% of highly effective schools for African American students.\nThe study also looked at three schools that are doing a phenomenal job of serving African American students.\nGet to know the schools:\n- <a href="/2011/10/watts-learning-center-in-los-angeles.html">Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles</a>\n- <a href="/2011/10/kipp-bridge-in-oakland.html">KIPP Bridge in Oakland</a>\n- <a href="/2011/10/st-hope-public-school-7-in-sacramento.html">PS7 in Sacramento</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/understanding/research/africanamericanreport/">Read the full report.</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/10/fact-sheet-chartering-and-choice-as-an-achievement-gap-closing-reform.html">Download a fact sheet to share with others.\n</a></p>\n', 'Charters Accelerate African American Student Achievement', 'A new report issued by the California Charter Schools Association found that charter schools are accelerating the achievement of African American students. Find out more and learn about three charter schools that are doing an exceptional job.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'charters_accelerate_african_american_student_achievement', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/charters_accelerate_african_american_student_achievement/', 0, 'post', '', 0) ;
