(107, 2, '2012-05-01 14:54:45', '2012-05-01 14:54:45', '<p>Was there an article about your school or charter schools in the local newspaper? Did you feel the reporter didn\'t get it right or that there is more to the story?\nWriting a letter to the editor of your local publication is a great way to raise awareness about your school and set the record straight.\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/04/letters-to-the-editor.html">See examples of letters written by parents and charter leaders.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Tips</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Be careful to keep a lid on your emotions, as a well-written and focused letter will be more likely to be published.</li>\n<li>All publications have a word maximum for submissions, generally between 150 and 200 words. Make sure you keep it short or the publication either won\'t run it or will edit your letter as they see fit.</li>\n<li>There are often opportunities to comment online immediately following an article on a publication\'s website. Go ahead and post your comments there, as well as submitting them to the editor.</li>\n<li>If you are responding to a story that already ran, also give the reporter who wrote the story a call or send an email to start building a relationship for future stories on local schools.</li>\n<li>Do you have more to say than what will fit in 150 words? Consider penning a guest editorial. The guest editorial or "op-ed" page is a coveted spot. Contact the editor of the publication, and discuss the potential for publishing your submitted story. A guest editorial should be succinct, well-researched, and timely. Publications will have a word maximum generally between 650 and 750 words per submission.</li>\n</ul>\n', 'How to Write a Letter to the Editor', 'Was there an article about your school or charter schools in the local newspaper? Writing a letter to the editor of your local publication is a great way to raise awareness about your school and set the record straight.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how_to_write_a_letter_to_the_editor', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/how_to_write_a_letter_to_the_editor/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(108, 2, '2012-05-01 15:01:18', '2012-05-01 15:01:18', '<p>Online forums give you an opportunity to defend yourself, share more information and get the word out. In this day and age, people get information from many different sources, and engaging online is key for building awareness of your school and building support.\n<strong>Most importantly, if someone writes bad things about you on an online forum, RESPOND.<sup>*</sup></strong></p>\n\n<h3>Why should I respond to an online post about my school?</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Much of what is posted on the web stays there indefinitely. People searching the internet will continue to find forums that are years old and have incorrect information.</li>\n<li>Responding to a nasty post can help set the record straight. At the very least, the response sows seeds of doubt in the reader\'s mind about whether the author of the original post is trustworthy.</li>\n<li>It starts a conversation. Just as you engage with the community face-to-face, social media, blogs and websites are a way to educate people about charter schools and to build support for your school.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Tips for engaging online</h3>\n\n<ul>\n<li>If you are mentioned online, whether positive or negative, encourage members of your community - teachers, staff, parents, or high school students to post their own comments and responses. Your parents are your best advocates!</li>\n<li>If you personally respond, be transparent about your relationship to the school, i.e.: "I am a parent at X school..." or "I work at X school. I would encourage anyone who is interested to visit our school. Contact us at XXX-XXXX."</li>\n<li>Share links that allow people to find out more and that verify what you\'re saying. For example:</li>\n<li>A link to your school\'s website</li>\n<li>A link to <a href="/understanding/">info for the public about charter schools from CCSA\'s website</a></li>\n<li>A link to media coverage of your school or the topic of the discussion</li>\n<li>Go beyond the newspaper. Articles on traditional media sites are a good place to start, but conversations are happening in many corners of the internet. For example:</li>\n<li>Yahoo! groups</li>\n<li>Facebook (Sometimes local businesses or organizations have a large following in their neighborhoods)</li>\n<li>Twitter</li>\n<li>Blogs (<a href="http://technorati.com/">Technorati</a> is a good place to search.)</li>\n<li>Google your school. This is a great way to find out WHERE people are talking about your school online and WHAT they\'re saying about you.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>When you SHOULD NOT respond to a post</h4>\n\n<p><sup>*</sup> Before responding, look at the website or blog and find out more about the author of the post. Do they often write about charters or education? Is their coverage completely one-sided? Is the forum a space that is open to different viewpoints? If the author is extreme in his or her views, responding can sometimes only serve to incur more vitriol. This is a judgment call to make on a case by case basis.</p>\n', 'How to Respond to Criticism Online', 'Has someone posted negative comments about your school online? There are many ways to engage other parents at your school to respond.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how_to_respond_to_criticism_online', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/how_to_respond_to_criticism_online/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(109, 2, '2012-05-01 15:15:18', '2012-05-01 15:15:18', '<p>Our elected representatives make decisions every day that affect our schools and our students, from a state legislator who proposes a bill that will hurt charter schools to a local school board member who is deciding whether to let a new charter school open in that district.\n<strong>When it comes to charter schools, YOU are the expert.</strong> You have a great story to tell and speaking out really makes a difference - so how do you get your voice heard? It used to be you had to get the media\'s attention to write a story that would reach a lot of people. Nowadays, with the Internet, you have the power to reach people directly in so many different ways.\nThis page has more questions than answers. Our goal is to give you the right questions to ask so you can come up with a great strategy to support your school by speaking out online and sharing your story and getting other parents at your school to do the same!\nKey Questions:\n<strong>WHAT</strong> is your goal?\n<strong>WHO</strong> do you want to reach?\n<strong>WHAT</strong> do you want to say?\n<strong>WHERE</strong> are conversations taking place online?\n<strong>HOW</strong> do you best make your voice heard?\n<a href="/FTC_Communications_plan_template.pdf">Use this printable handout to guide you through developing a strategy for your online advocacy and outreach.</a>\nIt\'s important to work closely with your school leader and other parents and staff so that everyone is well-coordinated, knows what to say and understands their role in the plan. Your approach will vary depending on who you\'re trying to reach and for what purpose.\nDon\'t have a specific campaign underway at your school right now? There are still a lot of great things you can do to support your school and all charter schools.\nMore resources:\n- <a href="/2012/05/how-to-respond-to-criticism-online.html">How to Respond to Criticism of Your School Online</a>\n- <a href="/2012/05/how-to-write-a-letter-to-the-editor.html">How to Write a Letter to the Editor</a>\n- <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/07/how-to-use-patchcom-to-get-out-the-good-word-about-your-school.html">How to Use Patch.com to Get Out the Good Word About Your School</a>\n- <strong>Media Outreach:</strong> Do you need help reaching out to local reporters? Just send an email to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a> and we\'re happy to lend a hand!</p>\n\n<h3>Get Inspired</h3>\n\n<p>Below, you will find a variety of examples of online communications from different charter schools across California.\n<strong>School Websites</strong>\nA professional website is key to establishing your school\'s brand. There are many companies that can help you design, post and maintain an attractive website at an affordable cost and without advanced technical skills.\nMake sure your website has both basic content that rarely changes such as an "About us" section, contact details and a list of board members, as well as space on your home page to highlight new content. Some schools have a news section on their front page like <a href="http://www.pucschools.org/">Partnerships to Uplift Communities</a>.\nYour website is a resource for many different audiences. The <a href="http://www.classicalacademy.com">Classical Academies web site</a> is made to be easy to navigate, with all the basic information front and center and a tab for current parents to find the updates relevant to them.\n<strong>Social Media</strong>\nSocial media refers to a wide variety of different websites, with seemingly new outlets popping up daily. What they share in common is they allow users to interact with the content and each other, facilitating online conversation. Having a presence on some of these sites can be a great way to raise awareness about your school and share good news with a broad audience.\nHere are some sites you might explore:\n- Facebook\n- Twitter\n- YouTube\n-  GreatSchools\n- MySpace\n- Yelp\n- Flickr\n- Utterli\n- Wikis\n- Meetup\n- Digg\nJust because you haven\'t heard of a site doesn\'t mean people in your community don\'t use it! Schools use social media in various ways.\nFor instance, Green Dot has links to <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/greendotschools">YouTube</a>, <a href="http://twitter.com/greendotschools">Twitter</a> and <a href="http://www.facebook.com/pages/Green-Dot-Public-Schools/89279457280">Facebook</a> prominently displayed on their <a href="http://www.greendot.org">web page</a>, including a box on the home page featuring the latest tweets.\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/#!/pages/Synergy-Academies/194559103836">Synergy Academies</a> uses Facebook as a way to stay in touch with alumni, board members and supporters. They do a great job of posting lots of photos, links to news coverage of the school and other updates on a regular basis. You can see many more schools\' Facebook pages in the "Favorite Pages" section of <a href="http://www.facebook.com/calcharters">CCSA\'s Facebook page</a>.\n<a href="http://www.greatschools.org/news/3138-schools-using-social-media.gs?page=1">This article</a> details more creative ways that schools have used social media, like promoting school events or sending out the daily cafeteria menu.\n<strong>Video</strong>\nMany schools produce a video about their school, which can be a fun way to promote the school. Here are a few different videos from: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QxZkHCAwup4">Larchmont Charter School in Los Angeles</a>, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Wjxi0snEu98">Envision Charter Schools in the Bay Area</a> and <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/cacharters#p/u/44/C-awbRJN3to">Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles</a>.\n<strong>Blogs</strong>\nA blog can also be a way to spread the good word and to integrate different voices from your school community. Blog are particularly well-suited to integrating photos and video or links to interesting news articles or web sites. You can write about any issue or success story at your school, or invite others to do so, including parents, students, teachers and boardmembers. This <a href="http://www.muellercharterschool.org/Blog/">blog from Mueller Charter School</a> in Chula Vista has posts from various people on a variety of subjects. The <a href="http://oxfordchampions.typepad.com/">blog for Oxford Preparatory Academy in Chino Valley</a> has lots of photos and updates on classroom projects. The <a href="http://schools20.rsed.org/">blog for Rocketship Education</a> has entries on a variety of hot topics in education reform.</p>\n', 'How To Get Your Voice Heard Online', 'Learn more about blogging and harnessing the power of social media as a parent advocate!\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how_to_get_your_voice_heard_online', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/how_to_get_your_voice_heard_online/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(110, 2, '2012-05-04 15:16:44', '2012-05-04 15:16:44', '<p><em>"I had to say something. I\'m the voice for my child and my school and if I don\'t, only the voices on the other side of the issues would be heard."</em></p>\n\n<div class="figure embedded-image right"><a rel="lightbox" href="/assets_c/2012/05/lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento-thumb-612xauto-3076.jpg" title="lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento.JPG"><img alt="lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento.JPG" src="/assets_c/2012/05/lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento-thumb-250x160-3076.jpg" width="250" height="160" class="mt-image-right" /></a></div>\n\n<p>On a Monday evening in late April, Lanie Holmer, a parent at <a href="http://www.westlakecharter.com/">Westlake Charter School</a> in Sacramento got an urgent email from the school\'s Executive Director Bob Capp asking parents to call legislators about the state budget. An Assembly Committee would be debating important proposals about charter school funding the very next day. Lanie regularly attended school meetings and knew first-hand how California\'s funding structure and budget cuts to schools were hurting her children\'s school. Not only do charter schools receive less funding overall, but unlike school districts, charter schools can\'t take out low-interest loans to help them through deferrals. Right now, the state is delaying over 30% of payments due to schools into the next year. Imagine if your employer told you to keep doing your work, but you wouldn\'t receive a paycheck for part of it until next year!\nShe asked what she could do that make a difference and the director said: "Come with us to the hearing!" Lanie shares what it was like as a parent to testify before an Assembly committee.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I\'ve only been to the capitol building twice and only as a tourist. I walked into the building and the first thing I saw was a huge throng of people and I was hoping they weren\'t there for the same meeting! I managed to find the committee room and sat down. They hadn\'t reached our item on the agenda yet, so I read over the materials and thought about what I would say.</p>\n  \n  <p>Our school is fiscally responsible and has healthy reserves. It\'s that we\'re not getting our money due to the deferrals. All public schools are going through this. What\'s unique to charters is that we don\'t have the same means to bridge that shortfall as other schools do and we also receive less funding overall. It\'s just not fair.  Many of the Governor\'s budget proposals to address this made a lot of sense.</p>\n  \n  <p>I knew I had to say something. I\'m the voice for my child and my school and if I don\'t, only the voices on the other side of the issues would be heard. I wanted to support our school.</p>\n  \n  <p>I\'m a founding parent at Westlake Charter, which opened in 2005. We have an emphasis on global awareness and connecting children to the world. We have amazing teachers and the highest test scores in our district. As parents, we volunteer as much as we can.</p>\n  \n  <p>I\'ve completed about 150 volunteer hours so far this year and I\'m not the only one. Many parents have done even more. Our teachers are dedicated to the success of our students. We believe in the school and want it to do well, but none of that can overcome the fact that there\'s no money in our coffers due to the deferrals. We work really hard with what we\'ve got, but there\'s only so much that parent volunteers can do.</p>\n  \n  <p>As I watched the meeting, what was interesting is that the committee chair was the only committee member there for the entire meeting. I didn\'t know the legislators could go in and out throughout the meeting! When they called for public comment, about 20 people stood up. Everyone that spoke was a director, a principal, school board member, or they represented the school districts, as well as a representative from the county treasurer. They all had a better grasp and understanding of the issues and laws than I did. Aside from the representatives from our school board and our business office, who are also parents at the school, there weren\'t any other parents at this meeting and I wasn\'t sure that I would have much to offer.</p>\n  \n  <p>When I stood up and said, "I\'m just a parent," I really felt the energy in the room change, that the members of the committee were actually listening to me. That made the three hours in that meeting worth it - at least they listened to what I had to say and I wasn\'t just another person in the line. They listened to me because I was a parent.</p>\n  \n  <p>I\'m glad I showed up and wished other parents could have come, but understood that the late notice made it difficult. I\'m glad I was there to be a parent voice. Even if you can\'t show up, call and email. Otherwise, they won\'t hear us. We have to speak up; these are our kids.</p>\n</blockquote>\n', 'A Parent\'s Eye View of State Politics', 'Charter parent Lanie Holmer testifies before the CA Assembly\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'a_parents_eye_view_of_state_politics', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/a_parents_eye_view_of_state_politics/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(111, 2, '2012-05-04 15:43:19', '2012-05-04 15:43:19', '<p>In late April,<a href="/2012/04/state-budget-demand-a-fair-share-for-charter-schools.html"> we asked you to speak out on the state budget</a> to support several items in the current budget that would help level the playing field to ensure that charter schools get their fair share of funding.\nParents and advocates from schools as far away as the <a href="http://www.altusinstitute.net/">Altus Institute in San Diego</a> testified in support of the charter school budget items in the Senate Budget Subcommittee on Education.\n<em>"I had to say something. I\'m the voice for my child and my school and if I don\'t, only the voices on the other side of the issues would be heard."</em> - Lanie Holmer, parent from Westlake Charter School\n- <a href="/2012/05/a-parents-eye-view-of-state-politics.html">Read her first-person account of testifying at an Assembly Committee meeting.</a>\n<strong>The calls, emails, and in person testimony made a difference.</strong>  The Senate Subcommittee took several positive actions, and left other items open to decide at a later date.  This means that all of the charter school items are either still alive or headed to the budget conference committee for further discussion. We\'ll continue to keep you posted!</p>\n', 'State Budget: Your Voice Made a Difference', 'Parents called, emailed and testified in person - and it made a difference!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'state_budget_your_voice_made_a_difference', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/state_budget_your_voice_made_a_difference/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(112, 2, '2012-05-08 14:56:55', '2012-05-08 14:56:55', '<p>Help us spread the word by including news from Families That Can in your school newsletter or on your website. <a href="/2011/07/families-that-can-promotion-kit.html">Our bilingual promotion kit makes it easy.</a> We\'ll also provide a short article that\'s ready to go every month in our weekly e-newsletter. Make sure you <a href="/join">sign up to receive it</a> if you don\'t already!</p>\n\n<h3>Are you registered to vote?</h3>\n\n<p>Your vote is your voice! It\'s exciting to participate in presidential elections every four years, but don\'t forget that your vote has tremendous impact at the local level, from local schools to city government and county initiatives.\nYou can easily register online or by picking up a form at your county elections office, library, or U.S. Post Office. Elections are handled by the California Secretary of State. Visit their web page at <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov">www.sos.ca.gov</a> to learn more or to find out if you\'re already registered.\nAnother way to make your voice heard is through Families That Can, a statewide organization of charter school parents. Learn more and sign up for a free parent e-newsletter at <a href="/join">www.familiesthatcan.org/join</a>.</p>\n\n<h3>¿Se ha registrado para votar?</h3>\n\n<p>¡Su voto es su voz! Es emocionante participar en las elecciones Presidenciales cada cuatro años, pero no se olvide de que su voto tiene un tremendo impacto a nivel local. Afecta decisiones sobre las escuelas locales, así como iniciativas de municipios y condados.\nUsted puede registrarse para votar en línea o puede también recoger un formulario en la oficina electoral de su condado, bibliotecas locales, u oficinas de correo. Las elecciones son administradas por la Secretaría del Estado de California. Visite su página web en <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/">www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/</a> para obtener más información o para averiguar si ya está registrado.\nLos votantes pueden obtener ayuda adicional en español llamando gratis a la línea especial de la Secretaría de Estado al (800) 232-VOTA (8682).\nOtra manera de asegurar de que su voz sea escuchada es involucrarse con Families That Can (Las Familias Si Pueden), una organización de padres de las escuelas chárter por todo el estado de California. Regístrese hoy para recibir su boletín electrónico gratis en <a href="/join">www.familiesthatcan.org/join</a>.</p>\n', 'May Newsletter Article: Have you registered to vote?', 'Help spread the word by running this short article in your parent newsletter encouraging everyone to register to vote!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'may_newsletter_article_have_you_registered_to_vote', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/may_newsletter_article_have_you_registered_to_vote/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(113, 2, '2012-05-08 15:31:49', '2012-05-08 15:31:49', '<p>Ayúdenos a difundir información mediante la inclusión de nuestras noticias en su boletín escolar o en su página web. Nosotros incluiremos un breve artículo en nuestro boletín todos los meses para hacer este proceso mucho más fácil para usted.</p>\n\n<h3>¿Se ha registrado para votar?</h3>\n\n<p>¡Su voto es su voz! Es emocionante participar en las elecciones Presidenciales cada cuatro años, pero no se olvide de que su voto tiene un tremendo impacto a nivel local. Afecta decisiones sobre las escuelas locales, así como iniciativas de municipios y condados.\nUsted puede registrarse para votar en línea o puede también recoger un formulario en la oficina electoral de su condado, bibliotecas locales, u oficinas de correo. Las elecciones son administradas por la Secretaría del Estado de California. Visite su página web en <a href="http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/">www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/</a> para obtener más información o para averiguar si ya está registrado.\nLos votantes pueden obtener ayuda adicional en español llamando gratis a la línea especial de la Secretaría de Estado al (800) 232-VOTA (8682).\nOtra manera de asegurar de que su voz sea escuchada es involucrarse con Families That Can (Las Familias Si Pueden), una organización de padres de las escuelas chárter por todo el estado de California. Regístrese hoy para recibir su boletín electrónico gratis en <a href="/join">www.familiesthatcan.org/join</a>.</p>\n', 'Noticias para su boletín informativo para padres para Mayo', 'Ayúdenos a difundir información mediante la inclusión de nuestras noticias en su boletín escolar o en su página web.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'noticias_para_su_boletin_informativo_para_padres_para_mayo', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/noticias_para_su_boletin_informativo_para_padres_para_mayo/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(114, 2, '2012-05-10 13:16:04', '2012-05-10 13:16:04', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento.JPG (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/05/lanie_holmer_parent_sacramento-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p><em>"Sabía que tenía que decir algo, soy la voz de mis hijas y de mi escuela y, si no lo hago, solamente se escucharán las voces del otro lado".</em>\nUn lunes por la mañana del pasado mes de abril, Lanie Holmer, una madre de familia de la escuela Westlake Charter School en Sacramento, recibió un correo electrónico urgente del director ejecutivo de la escuela, Bob Capp, en el que le pedía a los padres que llamaran a sus representantes en la Legislatura acerca del presupuesto estatal. Un Comité de la Asamblea debatiría propuestas importantes sobre el financiamiento de las escuelas chárter al día siguiente.\nLanie asistía con regularidad a las reuniones escolares y sabía por cuenta propia cómo la estructura de financiamiento de California, y los recortes en el presupuesto estatal, estaban impactando la escuela de sus hijas. Y es que las escuelas chárter no sólo reciben menos financiamiento que escuelas públicas tradicionales, sino que, a diferencia de los distritos escolares, las escuelas chárter no pueden obtener préstamos con bajos intereses para ayudarlas con  demoras en los fondos que reciben del estado. Actualmente, un 30% de los pagos que California le debe a las escuelas públicas--incluyendo a las escuelas chárter--está retrasado, y las escuelas no serán indemnizadas sino hasta el próximo año. Imagínense si su empleador les dijera que tienen que continuar haciendo su trabajo, pero que no van a recibir parte de su cheque ¡hasta el próximo año!\nLanie preguntó si su participación podría hacer una diferencia y el director le contestó: "¡Venga con nosotros a la audiencia!"\nLanie comparte lo que como madre testificó ante el Comité de la Asamblea.\nHe estado en el Capitolio Estatal sólo dos veces y nada más como turista. Al caminar dentro del edificio, lo primero que vi fue un enorme grupo de gente y pensé que ¡ojalá no estuvieran ahí para la misma reunión¡ Me las ingenié para encontrar el salón del comité y tomé mi asiento. No habían abordado todavía nuestro asunto en la agenda, así que leí los materiales y me puse a pensar en lo que iba a decir.\nNuestra escuela es fiscalmente responsable, y tiene reservas más que adecuadas.  Sin embargo, no está recibiendo el dinero que el estado le debe debido a retrasos. Todas las escuelas públicas están pasando por esto. La diferencia es que las escuelas chárter no tenemos los mismos medios para hacer frente a la escasez de fondos como otras escuelas y también recibimos en general menos financiamiento. Eso no es justo. Muchas de las propuestas en el plan de gasto del Gobernador Jerry Brown contemplan lidiar con este problema, y son muy lógicas.\nSabía que tenía que decir algo, soy la voz de mis hijas y de mi escuela y, si no lo hago, solamente se escucharán las voces del otro lado.\nSoy de los padres fundadores de la escuela Westlake Charter, la cual se inauguró en 2005. El plan de estudio de la escuela se enfoca en la conciencia global y en conectar a los niños con el mundo. Tenemos maestros muy destacados y las calificaciones más altas de nuestro distrito. Como padres, trabajamos como voluntarios lo más que se puede.\nPersonalmente, he completado 150 horas como voluntaria de la escuela tan sólo este año, y no soy la única. Muchos padres han hecho todavía más. Nuestros maestros están dedicados a lograr que todo estudiante tenga éxito en sus estudios.  Creemos en la misión y visión de nuestra escuela chárter, y queremos que salga adelante, pero no podemos dejar que nuestras aulas no cuenten con el financiamiento que necesitas, especialmente debido al constante retraso en los pagos que el estado le debe a las escuelas.  Trabajamos realmente duro con los recursos que tenemos, pero como padres voluntarios, no podemos hacer más.\nMientras miraba la reunión, me llamó la atención que el presidente del Comité fue el único que estuvo ahí todo el tiempo. ¡Yo no sabía que los Legisladores pueden entrar y salir durante la reunión! Cuando pidieron los comentarios del público, cerca de 20 personas se levantaron. Todos los que hablaron eran directores, miembros de la junta escolar o representantes de distritos escolares o tesoreros de condados. Todos tenían un mejor entendimiento de los asuntos y de las leyes que yo. Aparte de los representantes de nuestra junta escolar y de nuestra oficina de negocios, que también son padres de familia en la escuela, no había otros padres en la reunión y por ello yo no estaba segura si tenía que ofrecer algo de interés.\nCuando me levanté y dije: "Soy solamente una madre de familia", realmente sentí que la energía en el salón cambió, que los miembros del Comité realmente me estaban escuchando. Eso hizo que valieran la pena las tres horas que pasé en esa reunión, ya que por lo menos escucharon lo que tenía que decir y no fui sólo otra persona esperando para poder testificar.  Me escucharon porque soy una madre de familia.\nMe alegro de haber ido y hubiera deseado que otros padres también hubieran estado presentes, pero entiendo que el aviso de última hora dificultó eso. Estoy contenta de haber estado ahí para ser una voz de todos los padres que al igual que yo, llevan a sus hijos a escuelas chárter. Si ustedes no pueden ir a esas reuniones, por lo menos llamen o envíen un correo electrónico a sus Legisladores. De otra manera, ellos no nos van a escuchar, y no van a saber de las necesidades de nuestros hijos y nuestras escuelas chárter. Tenemos que hablar con una voz unida; se trata de nuestros niños.</p>\n', 'El punto de vista de una madre en el Capitolio Estatal', 'Lanie Holmer, madre de familia de una escuela chárter, testifica ante la Cámara Baja de la Legislatura de CA\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'el_punto_de_vista_de_una_madre_en_el_capitolio_estatal', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '2016-01-13 04:19:56', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/el_punto_de_vista_de_una_madre_en_el_capitolio_estatal/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(115, 2, '2012-05-10 14:02:03', '2012-05-10 14:02:03', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="maria_flores_parent_camino.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/05/maria_flores_parent_camino-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p><em>Maria Flores, segunda de la derecha, al lado de Monica Garcia</em>\nFamilies That Can (Las Familias Sí Pueden) felicitamos a todas las madres en su día, y esperamos que la pasen bien. El Día de las Madres llegó temprano para una de nuestros miembros y madre de una escuela chárter, María Flores.  Recientemente, Flores recibió un reconocimiento especial como "Madre Campeona" por parte de la Presidente de la Junta Directiva del Distrito Escolar de Los Angeles (LAUSD), Mónica García, en el tercero de los Premios Anuales de Guillermina. Esta ceremonia honra a mujeres excepcionales en Los Angeles que inspiran, apoyan y educan a nuestras comunidades. La ceremonia tuvo lugar el pasado miércoles, 9 de mayo 2012 en El Mercadito de Los Angeles.\nMaría Flores nació en la Ciudad de México. Con el apoyo de su familia, ella fue capaz de completar dos años de estudios superiores en Administración de Empresas con énfasis en Turismo, hasta que emigró a los Estados Unidos en 1989. Flores es una orgullosa madre de tres niños. Su hijo más joven es un estudiante de tercer grado que asiste a la escuela chárter Camino Nuevo Harvard, su hermano de 15 años de edad, es un estudiante de décimo grado en el Camino Nuevo High School, y su hijo mayor de 19 años es el orgullo de la familia - el primer miembro en ser aceptado en una Universidad. Actualmente se encuentra en su segundo año en la Universidad Estatal de Nuevo México.\nMaría dice que para educar a nuestros niños, se requiere de toda una comunidad, y es por eso regala el mayor tiempo posible como voluntaria en las escuelas de sus hijos. Ella ha pasado una gran cantidad de horas como voluntaria en la biblioteca de la escuela, ayudando en las aulas, la cafetería y más. María se convirtió en miembro de Families That Can a través de su papel como voluntaria activa en Harvard Elementary. María ha sido una campeona en la educación de la familia, amigos, la comunidad y los representantes electos, abogando para que la prioridad principal de todos sea el futuro de nuestros hijos. Ella ha viajado hasta Sacramento para abogar por todos nuestros niños, y por aquellos padres que no pueden votar, o que no pueden dejar su trabajo para poder hacer lo mismo.   María  es una verdadera "¡Madre Campeona!"\n- <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.344226602310132.80528.102530249813103&amp;type=3">Vea más fotos.</a></p>\n', 'Feliz Día de Las Madres a Una "Madre Campeona"', 'Maria Flores de la escuela chárter Camino Nuevo fue honrado esta semana por la Presidenta de la Junta Directiva del Distrito Escolar de Los Angeles\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'feliz_dia_de_las_madres_a_una_madre_campeona', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/feliz_dia_de_las_madres_a_una_madre_campeona/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(116, 2, '2012-05-10 14:05:28', '2012-05-10 14:05:28', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="maria_flores_parent_camino.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/05/maria_flores_parent_camino-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p><em>Maria Flores, second from the right, was honored by LAUSD Board President Monica Garcia, center</em>\nFamilies That Can would like to take this time to wish all mothers a very Happy Mother\'s Day.  Mother\'s Day came early for one of our faithful charter school parents, Maria Flores.  She was recently honored as a "Madre Campeona" (Champion Mother) by Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) Board president Monica Garcia at the 3rd Annual Guillermina Awards. This ceremony honors amazing women in Los Angeles that inspire, support and educate our communities. The ceremony took place on Wednesday, May 9, 2012 at El Mercadito De Los Angeles.\nMaria Flores was born in Mexico City.  With the support of her family she was able to complete two years of higher education in Business Administration with a focus on Tourism up until she immigrated to the United States in 1989.  She is a proud parent of three boys; her youngest son is a third grader who attends Camino Nuevo Harvard, her 15-year-old son is a tenth grader at Camino Nuevo High School, and her oldest son, 19, is her family\'s new pride and joy - the first member of their family to be accepted to a university. He is currently in his second year at New Mexico State University.\nMaria is a firm believer that it takes a village to raise a child, and that is why she is always volunteering in her children\'s schools.   She volunteers countless hours in the school library, classrooms, cafeteria and wherever else needed on campus.  Maria became an engaged member of Families That Can through her active volunteer role at Harvard Elementary.  Maria has been a champion in educating family, friends, community stakeholders and key legislative members that the key focus should be on our children\'s future.  She has rallied all the way to Sacramento to advocate for all our children who cannot vote, for all the parents who cannot vote and for all those parents that have to work countless hours to support their families.  She is a true "Madre Campeona!"\n- <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.344226602310132.80528.102530249813103&amp;type=3">See more photos.</a></p>\n', 'Happy Mother\'s Day to a "Champion Mother"', 'Maria Flores a parent from Camino Nuevo charter schools was recently honored by Los Angeles School Board member Monica Garcia\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'happy_mothers_day_to_a_champion_mother', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/happy_mothers_day_to_a_champion_mother/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(117, 2, '2012-05-23 14:53:03', '2012-05-23 14:53:03', '<p>Join the growing movement of PACT parents at their Community Action Meeting\nin partnership with Franklin McKinley School Board Members and the Superintendent\nThursday, May 31 at 6 p.m.\nSullivan Hall, St Maria Goretti Church\n2980 Senter Road, San Jose CA\n<em>"My worry is safety. I feel as if I can\'t protect Leonardo or Gerardo when I drop them off at school. I\'m also conscious of the fact that they are not receiving the education they should be, but they are my only options because they are my neighborhood schools."</em>\n- Mayela Razo, parent of Sylvandale and Daniel Lairon students\nPACT parents believe all children have the right to an excellent education no matter their economic status or ethnicity.\nUnfortunately, of all the students in Franklin McKinley School District, more than 50% are not proficient in English Language Arts and more than 45% are not proficient in Math.\nThat\'s why parents will collaborate with Franklin McKinley School Board Members and the Superintendent to bring about effective changes in ensuring that the school district reaches its goal of closing the achievement gap in all schools by 2020, and that there are more high-quality middle school options for families.\n- <a href="http://www.pactsj.org/">Learn more about PACT.</a>\n- <a href="https://www.facebook.com/events/374665405919256/">RSVP on Facebook.</a>\nFor more information, please contact <a href="mailto:fhatimapaulino@pactsj.org">Fhatima Paulino</a>, (408) 910-6309.</p>\n', 'May 31 in San Jose: Community Meeting on the Middle School Crisis', 'Join the growing movement of PACT parents at their meeting later this month, hosted in partnership with Franklin McKinley School Board Members and the Superintendent.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'may_31_in_san_jose_community_meeting_on_the_middle_school_crisis', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/may_31_in_san_jose_community_meeting_on_the_middle_school_crisis/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(118, 2, '2012-05-24 12:09:24', '2012-05-24 12:09:24', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="bullis_escuela_popular_garden_service_project.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/05/bullis_escuela_popular_garden_service_project-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>On Saturday, May 12, families from Bullis Charter School (BCS), Escuela Popular/Center for Training and Careers Family Learning Center (EP) and volunteers affiliated with Stanford University\'s Worldwide Day of Service, worked side by side to build a play area and garden at Escuela Popular charter school in East San Jose.\n- <a href="http://flic.kr/s/aHsjzozAqb">See great photos from the event.</a>\nThe enthusiastic group of volunteers began work at 9 a.m. on an empty 40 x 100 plot of dirt. By 4 p.m., the team had moved 7.5 tons of play yard sand, planted thirteen new fruit tree and veggie beds, and installed a custom built sandbox, balance beams, hang bars, and a state-of-the-art irrigation system for the renovated garden area. Jose Gonzales Ruiz, a father of three originally from Oaxaca, Mexico, works during the day as a carpenter and attended classes at Escuela Popular on Saturdays to earn his high school diploma. At 5 p.m., he was still working to finish the last planter bed for the apple trees. Despite being tired and hot, he refused to leave until he finished the last planter bed. "This is my school. I need to finish the work. This garden will be great for our school."\nOn Monday, May 14, EP\'s 150 children in day care were frolicking in and around a brand new 12 x 12 foot sandbox, swinging on the new tire swing, stepping around two log circles, and playing on their new hang bars and balance beams. In addition to enhancing playtime, there are plans to give students an opportunity to have hands on lesson in planting seedlings and seed germination in the new garden\'s custom made planter beds. By summer EP families expect to have enough organic fruits and vegetables to share with their neighbors.\n"Our new garden and play area are literally a dream come true for our school," said Escuela Popular High School Principal Gricelda Gonzalez.  "Thanks to the efforts of this amazing crew of volunteers and the many donors involved, we were able to see our vision for a safe, fun, play yard for our pre-schoolers become a reality.  Before they were walking around the track for recess!  The garden will be a tremendous asset, from a curriculum perspective as well as provide our families access to fresh produce.  It was an extraordinary gift and impressive to see everyone working along side one another for a shared goal."\nThe families that volunteered at Saturday\'s event also left with this first-hand experience of how working together can bring about significant positive change to a whole community. Service learning is a key component of BCS\' curriculum focusing on character development and bringing students out of the classroom and into their communities, working for change.\nThis community-building initiative at this East San Jose public charter school was a truly team effort that involved the hard work and generosity of various groups within the Bay Area. Led by BCS parents Millie Gong and Christina Mireles, who is Deputy Director of Escuela Popular, the event involved over 150 volunteers from Stanford, BCS, and EP. The Health Trust provided a $1,500 grant. Other organizations that donated material and/or monetary resources included:\n- The Village Gardner in San Carlos\n- Lyngso Garden Materials in Redwood City\n- Devil Mountain Nursery in San Ramon\n- Bullis Boosters Club (Bullis Charter School\'s Parent-Teacher Organization)\n- EdTec Business and Development Specialists for Charter Schools\n- DesigningByTheYard.com</p>\n\n<h3>About Escuela Popular</h3>\n\n<p>In 1986, this community-based grassroots school was created to address the growing need for English classes in East San Jose. Escuela Popular (EP) has evolved into a K-12 charter academy that serves students in Dual Language (K-8), High School (youth and adults) and Childcare Academies. EP is committed to providing meaningful learning experiences in a small school setting. EP serves 300 full-time youth students in grades K - 12. Additionally, over 1,000 adults are enrolled in the school to earn a high school diploma. Over 90% of the students are English language learners and 93% are eligible for the free and reduced lunch program. To accommodate student needs, EP offers classes during the day and in the evenings. Their site is located at 149 North White Road, San Jose, CA. Phone: (408) 275 7191</p>\n\n<h3>About Bullis Charter School</h3>\n\n<p>Bullis Charter School (BCS) is a K-8 public charter school serving the Los Altos School District (LASD) community. The charter school was founded in 2003 by Los Altos School District parents who were determined to have a high-quality public school option for their children following the closure of their local public school. Currently serving more than 450 students, BCS is the top-performing public charter elementary school in California. It equips its students with the skills needed to compete in a 21st century global environment, including Mandarin language instruction, leadership training and a focus on engineering and technology. Learn more at <a href="www.bullischarterschool.com">www.bullischarterschool.com</a>.</p>\n', 'Parents Come Together to Build Garden at San Jose Charter School', 'Families from Bullis and Escuela Popular charter schools recently came together to build a new school garden and play area for Escuela Popular.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'parents_come_together_to_build_garden_at_san_jose_charter_school', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/parents_come_together_to_build_garden_at_san_jose_charter_school/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(119, 2, '2012-06-01 10:30:59', '2012-06-01 10:30:59', '<p><a href="http://www.ccsa.org/advocacy/statewide/ab1172.html">AB 1172</a> which would allow school districts to deny charter schools based on a "negative fiscal impact" to the district, is scheduled to be heard by the Senate Education Committee on June 13.  Take five minutes today and tell key State Senators that you are opposed to this attack on charter public school growth.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="298" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Z9TRVoxXKt4" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>AB 1172 represents a dramatic threat to charter schools in California. Student needs should come first. Decisions on whether to approve a new charter school should be made on the quality of the charter petition and whether the school will help students in the community, not red herring fiscal arguments.\n<a href="http://www.votervoice.net/Core/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28914&amp;SiteID=-1">Stand up for California\'s charter schools and make your voice heard today!</a></p>\n', 'ACTION ALERT: Oppose AB 1172!', 'This bill, which represents a dramatic threat to charter school growth in CA, will be heard on June 13.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'action_alert_oppose_ab_1172', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/action_alert_oppose_ab_1172/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(120, 2, '2012-06-01 10:34:24', '2012-06-01 10:34:24', '<p>El proyecto de ley AB 1172, el cual permitiría a los distritos escolares negar la aprobación de nuevas escuelas chárter por "impacto monetario negativo" contra el distrito, tendrá su próxima audiencia en el Comité de Educación del Senado el próximo miércoles 13 de junio.  Tómese cinco minutos hoy mismo para pedirle a los Senadores Estatales que se opongan a este ataque contra el crecimiento de la escuelas públicas chárter.\nLa AB 1172 representa una amenaza grave para las escuelas chárter en California. Las necesidades de los estudiantes deben ser una prioridad.  Una escuela chárter debe ser aprobada basándose en la calidad de la petición y programa, y como beneficiaría a estudiantes en la comunidad, y no en argumentos monetarios que no son más que distracciones.\n<a href="http://www.votervoice.net/Core/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=828&amp;IssueID=28914&amp;SiteID=-1">¡Defienda a las escuelas chárter de California y hágase escuchar hoy mismo!</a></p>\n', 'ALERTA DE ACCION:  ¡Derrote la medida AB 1172!', 'Levante su voz antes de que finalice el año escolar\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'alerta_de_accion_derrote_la_medida_ab_1172', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/alerta_de_accion_derrote_la_medida_ab_1172/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(121, 2, '2012-06-01 14:00:15', '2012-06-01 14:00:15', '<p>¿Publicaron un artículo de su escuela o de las escuelas chárter en su periódico local? ¿Siente usted que el reportero no incluyó la información correcta o que fue insuficiente?\nEl escribir una carta al editor de su publicación local es una gran forma de dar a conocer su escuela y corregir el récord de lo que se publica.\nVea a continuación <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/04/letters-to-the-editor.html">ejemplos de cartas escritas por padres</a> y líderes de las escuelas chárter.</p>\n\n<h3>Consejos</h3>\n\n<p>Tenga cuidado de mantener bajo control sus emociones. Una carta bien escrita y enfocada tiene más posibilidades de que la publiquen.\nTodas las publicaciones tienen un número máximo de palabras que se permiten y que generalmente oscilan entre 150 y 200. Asegúrese de que la carta sea breve porque, de lo contrario, no la publicarán o la editarán de la forma que ellos crean más conveniente.\nHay muchas oportunidades para comentar en línea inmediatamente después de que se publica un artículo en una publicación digital. No se detenga, ponga sus comentarios y, al mismo tiempo, envíelos al editor.\nSi usted está respondiendo a un artículo que ya se publicó, llame o envíele un correo electrónico al reportero que lo escribió para iniciar una relación para futuras notas sobre las escuelas locales.</p>\n\n<h3>¿Tiene que decir más cosas que no caben en una carta de 150 palabras?</h3>\n\n<p>Considere entonces escribir un editorial como invitado. La página de columnistas invitados es un lugar codiciado. Contacte al editor de la publicación y discuta el potencial para publicar su comentario. Una columna de esta naturaleza debe ser concisa, bien investigada y oportuna. Las publicaciones ponen un límite máximo de entre 650 y 750 palabras por columna.</p>\n', 'Cómo escribir una carta al Editor', 'El escribir una carta al editor de su publicación local es una gran forma de dar a conocer su escuela y corregir el récord de lo que se publica.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'como_escribir_una_carta_al_editor', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '2016-01-13 04:19:55', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/como_escribir_una_carta_al_editor/', 0, 'post', '', 0) ;
