(159, 2, '2012-10-03 09:28:05', '2012-10-03 09:28:05', '<p>Oakland families are invited to join us for this free and fun community event.</p>\n\n<h3>20th Anniversary of Oakland Charter Schools</h3>\n\n<p>*From Military to Montessori, Arts to Science - 20 years of Providing High-quality, Public School Options to Families *\nOur schools\' success is our students\' success and we are so proud of what Oakland charter school students have accomplished. Twenty years after the first charter school opened, Oakland\'s 40 charter schools serve about a quarter of students, providing diverse, high-quality options to families. Join parents, students and educators as together we celebrate, rally and keep up the momentum for the next generation of students.</p>\n\n<h4>Date</h4>\n\n<p>Saturday, Oct. 13, 2012\n8 a.m. - Registration open\n9 a.m. - Celebratory Program Featuring:\n- Noel Gallo, Oakland Unified School District Board Member\n- Jorge Lopez, Executive Director of the Oakland Charter Academy (formerly Jingle Town Charter School), Oakland\'s first charter school\n- Parris Moore, musician and alumna of Oakland School for the Arts\n- Poet Chinaka Hodge and entertainment from The Getback band!\n10 a.m. - noon - Charter School Expo\nAll attendees will need to be registered and checked-in prior to entering the event, so make sure you leave enough time. The program will begin promptly at 9 a.m.</p>\n\n<h4>Location</h4>\n\n<p>Preservation Park\n1233 Preservation Park Way, Oakland, CA 94612\nThe event hall is located on Martin Luther King, Jr. Way between 12th and 14th Streets and three blocks from 12th Street/Oakland City Center BART. Free parking will be available.</p>\n\n<h3>Looking for a school?</h3>\n\n<p>Are you looking to learn more about local charter public schools? Looking for a new elementary, middle or high school that will better suit your child\'s learning needs and desires?\nCome learn more about our individual schools during our charter school expo! School representatives will be able to answer questions about their unique school programs, the history of the school and how to enroll.\nLatonya Hamilton, a parent at Vincent Academy, shares her tips for parents who are looking for a school!</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/ZYuMJbBwHgc?list=PLB96B633C42AA99E3&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Join us Oct. 13  in Oakland for the 20th Anniversary Celebration and Charter School Expo', 'Are you looking for a school for your children? Don\'t miss this chance to learn more about Oakland\'s diverse and extraordinary charter schools!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'join_us_oct_13_in_oakland_for_the_20th_anniversary_celebration_and_charter_school_expo', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/join_us_oct_13_in_oakland_for_the_20th_anniversary_celebration_and_charter_school_expo/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(160, 2, '2012-10-04 18:00:27', '2012-10-04 18:00:27', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="valieria_koss.JPG (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/10/valieria_koss-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n*Valieria joined Families That Can in August 2012 and works with parents and schools in the San Diego area and the Inland Empire as a Director of Family and Community Engagement.*\nOne of my earliest memories is of my mom fighting so hard to get me into an elementary school that was just a few blocks from my house.  I was refused admission because of our zip code and instead the school where I was assigned to attend kindergarten was one with not only the lowest test scores, but problems with drugs and violence on campus.   I was fortunate because my mom worked so hard and knew the impact a quality education can have on a child\'s life trajectory. Ultimately, I was able to enroll in quality public schools and go on to earn a Master\'s Degree while several of my neighborhood friends were not as lucky.  However, I grew up with the deep belief that a quality education should not be a right for some and an unattainable goal for others just because of where you live.  In order to put my beliefs into action, throughout my career I have partnered with agencies whose mission is providing quality education for all students.\nI\'ve worked with great organizations including Jumpstart (through AmeriCorps), Head Start (Neighborhood House Association) and Teach for America dedicated to ensuring quality education for all students from the Pre-K to High School level. I am extremely passionate about the charter school movement having taught for several years in a charter school in New Orleans, Louisiana.  Commitment, dedication and a belief that every child can succeed when given an opportunity makes me thrilled to join the amazing team at FTC and CCSA.  I have also served as a Government Relations Liaison in Southern California and Washington D.C. for the National Multiple Sclerosis Society (NMSS). In this role, I particularly enjoyed developing partnerships with elected officials and their staff and to have parents and community members engage legislators in productive dialogue. While earning my Master\'s Degree in Public Policy, I focused my research projects on examining socio-economics/race and education in Southern California and abroad.\nWhile I love working with students; parents can often be one of my favorite groups of people.  I can think of no one as passionate and motivated to ensure that students receive a quality education than parents.  Giving them the tools and confidence they need to become impactful advocates is one of the most exciting parts of my job at Families That Can.  The partnerships we can create with parents will have such a dramatic impact not only on the lives of their own children, but really all students.  Visiting school sites and meeting the innovative and passionate teachers and charter leaders as well as the parents and students committed to education makes every day even better than the day before. There is so much passion and innovation in charter schools in San Diego and the Inland Empire and I am thrilled to be able to help share and shape this movement. My mom has been such a role model for me. I\'m excited for students to witness first-hand their own parents finding their voice and having an impact on the education movement.\n', 'Meet Valieria Koss', 'FTC\'s New Parent Organizer for San Diego!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'meet_valieria_koss', '', '', '2012-10-04 18:00:27', '2012-10-04 18:00:27', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=160', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(161, 2, '2012-10-09 14:18:20', '2012-10-09 14:18:20', '<div class="figure embedded-image right"><img alt="saul_guzman_olga_mohan_parent_la.JPG" src="/saul_guzman_olga_mohan_parent_la.JPG" width="320" height="240" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></div>\n\n<p>Recently, <a href="/2012/09/action-alert-la-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-to-stop-charter-schools-and-take-away-parent-choice.html">Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) Board Member Steve Zimmer made a proposal to limit the growth of charter schools in LA</a>. I\'d like to share my story and ask the LAUSD board to listen to the parents and vote no on this resolution.\nMy name is Saul Guzman and I\'m a proud parent at Dr. Olga Mohan Charter High School in Downtown Los Angeles CA, a charter public school where my son is now a 9th grader. I had my son at a private school in Los Angeles for eight years, and he wanted to continue to study at a private high school because of the horrible stories he heard about public schools.  People said that public schools are full of gangsters, they do drugs, the students do not respect their teachers, etc. I was not sure what to do because I wanted the best for my son, so I applied for two well-known private high schools in the Los Angeles area and my son was accepted, but to my surprise, they were so expensive that I could not afford them.  For this reason, I researched on the internet for the best public high school possible. I found Dr. Olga Mohan as the best possibility and was lucky enough that they accepted my son just in time for the school year.\nI have volunteered since the first day of class for pedestrian and traffic control. During this time, I noticed how the whole staff was involved with the students, the teachers have a great rapport with them, the teachers are very respectful, professional and very accommodating, Also the students are very respectful and conduct themselves in a professional manner.\nThis school also has high academic expectations. When my son was at private school, I remember, they were coached only twice in a quarter and it was totally up to the parents\' and students\' choice whether to pass or fail a subject. At Dr. Olga\'s school, the student counselors get very involved with not only the kids but with their parents toward the success of the student. At Dr. Olga School they provide support classes, mandatory tutoring after school, they provide all the necessary tools for the student not to be left behind.  At Dr. Olga Mohan School, the slogan "No kid is left behind" is a true statement.\nThis is my first year as a parent at a public school, but I\'m very impressed with the hard work and dedication from the personnel at Dr. Olga Charter High School.\nFrom the many conversations that I had with parents and teachers at Dr. Olga\'s Charter school, they are very excited as well about sharing the success they\'ve found at this school, 100% of seniors graduated from this school last year, attended college this year.  The school had earned academic awards since first year when opened and parents are even more excited about the great work ahead as Dr. Olga Mohan continues to grow.\n- <a href="/2012/09/action-alert-la-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-to-stop-charter-schools-and-take-away-parent-choice.html">Take action here to tell the LAUSD board to vote against this resolution!</a>\n<em>Saul Guzman is a parent at Dr. Olga Mohan Charter School, which was the 2011 Charter School of the Year.</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/s6JY1fbHwlU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Parent Voice: Saul Guzman: "I wanted the best for my son"', '"I wanted the best for my son," says Los Angeles parent Saul Guzman, who recently spoke out against a proposal to stop all charter school growth in LA and shares his personal experiences.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'parent_voice_saul_guzman_i_wanted_the_best_for_my_son', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/parent_voice_saul_guzman_i_wanted_the_best_for_my_son/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(162, 2, '2012-10-09 16:29:47', '2012-10-09 16:29:47', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="valieria_koss.JPG (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/10/valieria_koss-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n*Valieria se unió a Families That Can (Las Familias Si Pueden) en septiembre de 2012, y trabaja con los padres y las escuelas en el área de San Diego como Directora de Participación Familiar y Comunitaria.*\nUno de mis primeros recuerdos es de mi mamá luchando muy duro para que pudiera entrar en una escuela primaria que estaba a sólo unas cuadras de mi casa. Se me negó la admisión a causa de donde vivíamos, y por consecuente, me asignaron una escuela para asistir al kínder que tenía no sólo bajo rendimiento académico, pero problemas con drogas y violencia.  .  A mí me tocó suerte porque mi mamá sabía el impacto que una buena educación puede tener en la vida de una persona.   Al fin de cuentas, tuve la oportunidad de asistir a  escuelas públicas de alta calidad e hice mi maestría en la universidad, mientras que varios de mis amigos se quedaron atrás.  Sin embargo, yo crecí con la profunda convicción de que una educación de calidad no debe ser un derecho para unos cuanto, y una meta inalcanzable para los demás, ni tampoco debe ser dictada por el lugar donde uno vive.   Es por eso que a lo largo de mi carrera, he colaborado con agencias cuya misión es proporcionar una educación de alta calidad para todo estudiante.\nHe trabajado con grandes organizaciones, incluyendo Jumpstart (a través de AmeriCorps), Head Start (Neighborhood House Association) y Teach for America. Como profesional y persona, me apasionan las escuelas chárter y su misión, especialmente después de haber fungido como maestra en una escuela chárter in Nuevo Orleans, Louisiana.   Estoy emocionada de unirme al equipo increíble de Families That Can/Las Familias Sí Puede por su compromiso, su dedicación y nuestra meta común de lograr que todo niño pueda tener la oportunidad de asistir a una buena escuela, y tener éxito en sus vidas.  En el pasado, también trabajé en Relaciones Gubernamentales con los   en el Sur de California y Washington D.C. para la Sociedad Nacional de Esclerosis Múltiple (SMN). En esta posición, tuve la oportunidad de conectar a funcionarios electos y su personal con padres de familia y miembros de la comunidad  afectados por esta enfermedad, para poder crear un diálogo productivo. Mientras cursaba mi Maestría en la Política Pública, centré mis proyectos de investigación en los vínculos entre la clase social y la etnia de una persona,  con la educación en el Sur de California y en el extranjero.\nAunque me gusta trabajar con estudiantes, también me encanta trabajar con padres de familia. Los padres tienen una pasión y motivación incalculable para que sus hijos reciban una buena educación.  Una de las partes más emocionantes de mi trabajo con Families That Can es dar a los padres las herramientas, los recursos y la confianza que necesitan para tener un impacto positivo como defensores de la educación pública y las escuelas chárter. Pueden tener un gran impacto no sólo en la vida de sus propios hijos, sino también en la educación que reciben todos los estudiantes en California. Cada día es aún mejor que el día anterior porque tengo la oportunidad para visitar escuelas, conocer a maestros innovadores y apasionados, así como a padres y estudiantes comprometidos con la educación. Hay tanta pasión e innovación en las escuelas chárter de San Diego e  Inland Empire, y me siento feliz de poder ser parte de este movimiento. Mi madre ha sido un modelo a seguir para mí. Estoy emocionada de ver que los estudiantes tendrán la oportunidad ver a sus propios padres encontrar su voz, para que tengan  un impacto en el movimiento de la educación pública.\n', 'Conozca a Valieria Koss', 'Valieria se unió a Families That Can (Las Familias Si Pueden) en septiembre de 2012, y trabaja con los padres y las escuelas en el área de San Diego como Directora de Participación Familiar y Comunitaria.\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'conozca_a_valieria_koss', '', '', '2012-10-09 16:29:47', '2012-10-09 16:29:47', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=162', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(163, 2, '2012-10-19 10:16:03', '2012-10-19 10:16:03', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) is launching a Start-Up Circle! You are invited to join other educators, parents, and community leaders to discuss the process of starting a charter school and the landscape throughout Sacramento County - existing schools, demand for new schools, and more.\nYou\'ll have the opportunity to share ideas, talk with Penny Schwinn (Founder &amp; Head of School, Capitol Collegiate Academy, and Trustee, Sacramento County Board of Education), learn about supports available to teams interested in starting a school, and connect with others who also want to see more high-quality schools in Sacramento County.\nThe first event will be held on October 24 at 6:30 p.m. at the Teach For America Sacramento Offices, 3400 3rd Avenue, Sacramento. <a href="/Start-Up_Circle_Sacramento_10-24-12.pdf">Download a printable flyer.</a>\nPlease feel free to share this information with others and <a href="www.meetup.com/startupcircle">don\'t forget to RSVP here</a>!\nCan\'t make it? <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/starting/">Learn more about how to start a charter school!</a></p>\n', 'Oct. 24: You\'re invited to Start-up Circle in Sacramento', 'Have you ever wondered about how to start a charter school? Or how to bring a great new charter school to your neighborhood? Don\'t miss this great event!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'oct_24_youre_invited_to_start-up_circle_in_sacramento', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/oct_24_youre_invited_to_start-up_circle_in_sacramento/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(164, 2, '2012-10-19 16:52:47', '2012-10-19 16:52:47', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) is launching a Start-Up Circle in the Bay Area! You are invited to join other educators, parents, and community leaders to learn more about the process of starting a charter school and to discuss the landscape throughout the Bay Area - existing schools, demand for new schools, and more.\nYou\'ll have the opportunity to share ideas, talk with the inspiring founders of <a href="http://www.vincentacademy.org/">Vincent Academy</a> -- Jean Driscoll (Board President, Vincent Academy) and Kate Nichol (Head of School, Vincent Academy), learn about supports available to teams interested in starting a school, and connect with others who also want to see more high-quality schools in the Bay Area.\nThis event will be held on November 8 at 6:30 p.m. at the Oakland School for the Arts, 530 18th Street, Room 315, Oakland. <a href="http://www.meetup.com/startupcircle/events/83338242/">Please RSVP on Meet-up!</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/H3oCQToUT1Q?list=PL5475BDBA283F57CC&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Nov. 8: You\'re invited to Start-up Circle in the Bay Area', 'Have you ever wondered about how to start a charter school? Or how to bring a great new charter school to your neighborhood? Don\'t miss this great event in Oakland!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'nov_8_youre_invited_to_start-up_circle_in_the_bay_area', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/nov_8_youre_invited_to_start-up_circle_in_the_bay_area/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(165, 4, '2012-11-02 16:10:59', '2012-11-02 16:10:59', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) announced this month that 109 charter schools opened across the state for the 2012-13 school year. This brings the total number of charter schools in California to 1,065. In addition, the number of students enrolled in charter schools grew to 484,000. This growth comes despite intense funding, facilities and authorizing challenges faced by charter schools.\n"In this year when we are celebrating the 20th Anniversary of the charter school movement in California, we are seeing the movement experience another spike in momentum as parents and communities across the state turn to charter schools in ever greater numbers," said Jed Wallace, President and CEO of CCSA.\nThis school year, Los Angeles County had the largest charter school growth with 40 new charters, followed by 12 new charters in Sonoma County, ten in San Diego County, and six Alameda County.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/2012/10/2012-13-new-schools-press-kit.html">Learn more and see the full press release.\n</a></p>\n', 'California Charter Schools Grow to More Than 1,000', 'More than 484,000 charter students statewide\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'california_charter_schools_grow_to_more_than_1000', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/california_charter_schools_grow_to_more_than_1000/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(166, 4, '2012-11-02 16:14:21', '2012-11-02 16:14:21', '<p>Every day, our elected officials make major decisions that affect our schools and our children. Your vote is your voice. Every single vote really does count and the stakes couldn\'t be higher for our schools.\nVote yes on Prop. 30! If this proposition doesn\'t pass, there will be an automatic trigger cut of $5 billion to education - $460 per student.\nStill undecided on local school board candidates? Check out our <a href="/voterguides">informational voter guides</a> for San Diego, Oakland and several Sacramento area districts!\nAfter you vote, visit our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/familiesthatcan">Facebook page</a> to get your virtual "I voted today!" sticker to spread the words to friends and family!</p>\n', 'Vote on Tuesday, Nov. 6!', 'Your vote is your voice!\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'vote_on_tuesday_nov_6', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/vote_on_tuesday_nov_6/', 0, 'post', '', 0) ;
