(390, 8, '2015-10-28 14:31:37', '2015-10-28 14:31:37', '<p>Three months into its first school year, Lighthouse Charter School in West Sacramento is already expanding students\' horizons. Recently the school took its kids on a field trip to nearby Clarksburg, where they got lessons in food and agriculture from local farmers. By bringing students face-to-face with real world community issues and industries, the school is ensuring that student learning goes beyond the pages of their textbooks.</p>\n', 'Sacramento Charter Students Learn from Local Farmers', 'A field trip to the local farm is the type of activity that makes Lighthouse Charter School unique and keeps students inspired.\r\n', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'sacramento_charter_students_learn_from_local_farmers', '', '', '2016-01-19 05:26:28', '2016-01-19 05:26:28', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/sacramento_charter_students_learn_from_local_farmers/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(391, 8, '2015-10-28 14:32:37', '2015-10-28 14:32:37', '<p>Charter schools are public schools, but that hasn\'t stopped the city council in Richmond from trying to charter students from participating in a crucial college scholarship opportunity that was supposed to include all public school kids. So the charter community has been rallying tirelessly for months to make sure their elected officials do the right thing. At the most recent city council meeting, charter supporters stayed until nearly midnight, pressuring the council to vote to include charters in the "Richmond Promise." The council delayed voting, so charter folks will keep pushing their leaders to include them. Stay tuned for the next update.</p>\n', 'Richmond Parents Keep Fighting for Educational Justice', 'The city council still won\'t commit to including charter students in a public college scholarship program, but charter families won\'t back down\r\n', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'richmond_parents_keep_fighting_for_educational_justice', '', '', '2016-01-19 05:25:01', '2016-01-19 05:25:01', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/richmond_parents_keep_fighting_for_educational_justice/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(392, 8, '2015-10-29 15:39:12', '2015-10-29 15:39:12', '<p><figure class="figure-full figure-border"><a rel="lightbox" href="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/IMG_1336-300x225-thumb-300x225-6307.jpg" title="Thumbnail image for Lighthouse Charter at Local Farm"><img alt="Thumbnail image for Lighthouse Charter at Local Farm" src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/IMG_1336-300x225-thumb-300x225-6307-thumb-300x225-6309.jpg" width="300" height="225" class="mt-image-none" /></a></figure> Tres meses después de comenzar su primer año escolar, la Escuela Chárter Lighthouse de West Sacramento ya está abriendo horizontes a sus estudiantes. Recientemente la escuela llevó a sus niños a una excursión al pueblo cercano de Clarksburg, donde recibieron lecciones de la comida y la agricultura de agricultores locales. Por acercar a los estudiantes a los temas comunitarios e industrias del mundo verdadero, la escuela está asegurando que el aprendizaje estudiantil vaya más allá de las páginas de sus libros de texto.</p>\n', 'Estudiantes chárter de Sacramento aprenden de agricultores locales', 'Una excursión a la finca local es el tipo de actividad que le hace especial a la Escuela Chárter Lighthouse y les mantiene inspirados a sus estudiantes.\r\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'estudiantes_charter_de_sacramento_aprenden_de_agricultores_locales', '', '', '2016-01-13 21:50:59', '2016-01-13 21:50:59', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/estudiantes_charter_de_sacramento_aprenden_de_agricultores_locales/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(393, 8, '2015-10-29 15:46:08', '2015-10-29 15:46:08', '<p><figure class="figure-full figure-border"><a rel="lightbox" href="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/Richmond%20students%20-%20Richmond%20Promise-thumb-3264x2448-6306-thumb-638xauto-6308.jpeg" title="Thumbnail image for Richmond students - Richmond Promise.jpeg"></p>\n\n<div data-picture data-alt="Thumbnail image for Richmond students - Richmond Promise.jpeg">\n  <div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/Richmond%20students%20-%20Richmond%20Promise-thumb-3264x2448-6306-thumb-385xauto-6308.jpeg">\n  </div>\n  \n  <div data-src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/Richmond%20students%20-%20Richmond%20Promise-thumb-3264x2448-6306-thumb-3264xauto-6308.jpeg" data-media="(min-width: 481px)">\n  </div>\n  \n  <noscript>\n    <img src="http://www.ccsafamilies.org/assets_c/2015/10/Richmond%20students%20-%20Richmond%20Promise-thumb-3264x2448-6306-thumb-385xauto-6308.jpeg" alt="Thumbnail image for Richmond students - Richmond Promise.jpeg" />\n  </noscript>\n</div>\n\n<p></a></figure> Las escuelas chárter son escuelas públicas, pero eso no ha parado al consejo municipal en Richmond de tratar de impedir que los estudiantes chárter participen en una oportunidad importante para recibir becas universitarias que supuestamente tenía que incluir a todos los niños de las escuelas públicas. Entonces la comunidad chárter ha estado manifestando sin cansar por meses para asegurar que sus oficiales elegidos hagan lo correcto. En la reunión más reciente del consejo municipal, los partidarios chárter se quedaron hasta casi la medianoche, dándole presión al consejo para votar por la inclusión de las escuelas chárter en la "Promesa de Richmond." El consejo aplazó el voto, entonces la gente chárter va a seguir exigiendo a sus líderes que las incluyan.</p>\n', 'Padres de Richmond siguen luchando para la justicia educativa', 'El consejo municipal todavía no se comprometerá a incluir a los estudiantes chárter a un programa de becas de universidades públicas, pero las familias chárter no se darán por vencidas.\r\n', 'trash', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'padres_de_richmond_siguen_luchando_para_la_justicia_educativa', '', '', '2016-01-13 05:37:08', '2016-01-13 05:37:08', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/padres_de_richmond_siguen_luchando_para_la_justicia_educativa/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(394, 8, '2015-10-29 15:58:03', '2015-10-29 15:58:03', '<p>The scene is becoming more common. Each month at the meeting of the school board of the Los Angeles Unified School, District make hundreds of families outside row only for the chance to tell the board how much care about their schools. That is precisely what happened to the meeting this month, parents and students in charter schools Aspire, Camino Nuevo and Green Dot met to ensure that the board voted to renew its charter schools. And that is exactly what made the meeting. L.A. Live charter families! Families are also spreading the word about a substantial problem facing schools of LA: the search for the next superintendent. By filling out hundreds of surveys and attending public meetings, parents and students in charter schools are ensuring that the school board know that the next superintendent must support charter schools and school choice. It is expected that the school board chooses the next superintendent for later this year</p>\n', 'L.A. Families Flex Their Advocacy Muscle', 'The scene is becoming more common. Each month at the meeting of the school board of the Los Angeles Unified School, District make hundreds of families outside row only for the chance to tell the board how much care about their schools.', 'trash', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'familias_de_la_flexionan_sus_musculos_de_promocion', '', '', '2016-01-13 22:07:28', '2016-01-13 22:07:28', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/familias_de_la_flexionan_sus_musculos_de_promocion/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(395, 8, '2015-11-17 11:17:38', '2015-11-17 11:17:38', 'L.A. charter families: we need your help. Will you stand up and speak out on behalf of all charter families, teachers and schools? On December 8th, the L.A. Unified school board will consider opposing a plan to expand parent choice and increase the number of charter schools. This resolution would strike at the heart of the charter school movement, putting politics before students and families.\nCan you join us for a major action at L.A. Unified headquarters in downtown L.A. to tell the board not to stand in the way of parents\' right to educational choice? Join hundreds of parents like you who know that charter schools are crucial for their children\'s success. To get involved, please contact parent organizer Esmeralda Marcial at emarcial@calcharters.org.\nIf you can\'t make it December 8th, please sign _____.\n', 'L.A. Families: Join Us for Action December 8th', 'Tell the L.A. school board -- in person -- why charter schools are crucial for student success.\n', 'draft', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'la_families_join_us_dec_8th_for_action', '', '', '2015-11-17 11:17:38', '2015-11-17 11:17:38', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=395', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(396, 8, '2015-11-17 12:21:03', '2015-11-17 12:21:03', '<p>If you\'re a charter parent, you\'re part of a fast-growing statewide movement. Want proof? More than half a million students -- an estimated 581,100 -- are now enrolled in charter schools across California. An additional 80 new charters statewide opened their doors this year, bringing the total number of charters to 1,230. California remains the state with the greatest number of charter schools, and the most students enrolled in charters, anywhere in the country. This growth shows that charter schools are providing the type of education that parents and students want and need. For more info on charter school growth in California, &#91;check out this fact sheet&#93;(http://www.ccsa.org/blog/2015-16_NewSchools_CA_FactSheet__.pdf).</p>\n', 'Record Number of California Students Choose Charters', 'Did you know that over half a million students are enrolled in charter schools across the state?\r\n', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'record_number_of_california_students_choose_charters', '', '', '2016-01-20 22:59:43', '2016-01-20 22:59:43', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=396', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(397, 8, '2015-01-17 13:58:12', '2015-01-17 13:58:12', '<p>After months of publicly fighting for fairness in Richmond\'s college scholarship program, charter families have won a huge victory. The city council voted to include charter schools in the $35 million Richmond Promise, which will provide college scholarship aid to every senior graduating from a public high school who is enrolling in a college or university. If it seems like a no brainer that charter students should be included in a program designed to help all public school students afford college, it <em>is</em>. Yet, unfortunately, many of the elected officials wanted to exclude charters until parents, students, teachers and community members fought back and demanded equality for <em>all</em> public school students. For months, the Richmond city council and Mayor Tom Butt tried to dodge the issue, and several times nearly voted to deny charters. But charter families rallied at every city council meeting and even protested outside the mayor\'s office. Their actions generated lots of <a href="http://www.contracostatimes.com/richmond/ci_29034917/richmond-no-decision-reached-college-assistance-program">media attention</a>, which reminded the politicians that they were being watched. Finally, the council voted and did the right thing for all students. Congratulations to Richmond charter families on a hard-fought and inspiring victory!</p>\n', 'Victory for Richmond Charter Families!', 'After months of parents and students demanding equality in the city\'s college scholarship program, the city council has voted to include charter students.\r\n', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'victory_for_richmond_charter_families', '', '', '2016-01-21 01:10:49', '2016-01-21 01:10:49', '', 0, 'http://192.168.20.50/wp/?p=397', 0, 'post', '', 0),
