(769, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p>Use this template as an article in your school\'s parent newsletter announcing your partnership and encouraging parents to sign up for FTC\'s free e-newsletter!</p>\n\n<h3>SCHOOL NAME partners with Families That Can</h3>\n\n<p>SCHOOL NAME announces that it has partnered with Families That Can (FTC), a statewide organization of charter school families. Every day, politicians make decisions that affect our school. Families That Can gives parents the tools and support you need to make sure your voice is heard. They will work with our school around issues like making sure we get our fair share of state money and the suitable school buildings and classrooms we need, as well as making sure we have the freedom to run our school in a way that meets our community\'s needs.\nMake sure you sign up to receive all the latest updates at /join - it\'s free! Families That Can regularly sends out updates on proposed laws that would affect your school, action alerts and invitations to events and workshops. You can also keep up with the latest by following with Families That Can on Twitter (@familiesthatcan) and Facebook (www.facebook.com/familiesthatcan). We are excited to work with Families That Can to make sure our elected leaders hear the voice of charter school families!</p>\n\n<h3>NOMBRE DE LA ESCUELA  anuncia alianza con Families That Can</h3>\n\n<p>Me complace anunciar que NOMBRE DE LA ESCUELA  se ha asociado con Families That Can (Las Familias Sí Pueden),  una organización a nivel estatal de padres de las escuelas chárter. Cada día, los políticos toman decisiones que tienen un gran impacto en nuestra escuela. Families That Can ayuda a los padres para que su voz sea escuchada. Van a trabajar con nuestra escuela para asegurar que nuestra escuela obtenga suficiente dinero estatal y los edificios escolares adecuados, así como los salones de clase que necesitamos y asegurarnos de que tenemos la libertad para dirigir nuestra escuela de manera que cumpla con las necesidades de nuestra comunidad.\nPara obtener información sobre los talleres que se organizarán próximamente y sobre noticias importantes, por favor inscríbanse en www.familiesthatcan.org/inscribase - ¡es gratis! Exploren el sitio en Internet de  Families That Can y  para más información. También se pueden conectar con Families That Can en las redes sociales de Twitter (@familiesthatcan) y Facebook (www.facebook.com/familiesthatcan).\n¡Estamos muy entusiasmados de trabajar con Families That Can para asegurarnos de que nuestros líderes electos puedan escuchar las voces de las familias de las escuelas chárter!\n*Families That Can provides a short article that you can use for your parent newsletter every month - look for it in our monthly newsletter! This is a great way to keep parents up to date and engaged.</p>\n', 'Parent Newsletter Template to Announce Partnership with Families That Can', 'Use this template as an article in your school\'s parent newsletter announcing your partnership and encouraging parents to sign up for FTC\'s free e-newsletter!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '105-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 105, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/105-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(770, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association has compiled answers to many frequently asked questions regarding charter schools and what they mean for students, educators, schools and communities.\n<strong>What are charter schools?</strong>\nCharters schools are public schools. They are tuition-free and open to any student who wishes to attend. Charter schools allow parents, organizations, or community groups to restore, reinvent, and reenergize our public school system. Charter schools are designed, tailored, and governed by each local community, rather than by a central bureaucracy.\n<strong>Are charters public schools?</strong>\nYes, charter schools are tuition-free, public schools that operate independently from the school district\'s central bureaucracy. Each charter school is governed by its own local school community, which often includes parents and teachers - rather than a district. This freedom allows teachers to be more innovative, and communities to shape their local school.\n<strong>How can I apply for a charter school? Are there admission requirements?</strong>\nCharter schools are open to ALL children and they are committed to serving a student body that reflects the local community. By law, charter schools can never have selective admissions; anyone can apply and, if more students want to attend than there are seats available, there is a lottery to determine who is admitted.\n<strong>Does it matter where I live? What is the attendance boundary?</strong>\nAs schools of choice, all charter schools are open to any student who wants to apply, regardless of where he or she lives, space permitting. Independent Study or non-classroom based schools have some geographical limitations such as only being open to students from a specific county.\n<strong>How does the lottery system work?</strong>\nCharter schools are open to all students who want to attend, regardless of where they live. If the school receives more students than for which it has spots available, it is required by law to hold a blind lottery to determine which students will have the opportunity to attend. Many charter schools have wait lists and may admit more students as spots become available.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/understanding/faqs/">Click here for more FAQs and to download a fact sheet.</a></p>\n', 'Charter School FAQs', 'The California Charter Schools Association has compiled answers to many frequently asked questions from students, educators, schools and communities regarding charter schools.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '27-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 27, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/27-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(771, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p>Get to know some of the amazing and diverse charter schools in Oakland and the Bay Area.</p>\n\n<h2>Oakland Charter Academy</h2>\n\n<p><em>The California Charter Schools Association named this school "Charter School of the Year" in 2009 for its amazing work to prepare students for college.</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe title="YouTube video player" width="480" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/vQWmni5mcbI" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<h2>Aspire Public Schools</h2>\n\n<p><em>Aspire runs more than 30 high-performing schools across California, including several in the Bay area. Their motto is "College for Certain."</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe title="YouTube video player" width="480" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/H-76mCxccsY" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<h2>KIPP Schools</h2>\n\n<p><em>KIPP (Knowledge is Power Program) has schools across the country focused on helping low-income students go to college.</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe title="YouTube video player" width="480" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/rVi07IxmVkg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<h2>Envision Schools</h2>\n\n<p><em>Envision runs four schools in California - hear what one student had to say about her experience.</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe title="YouTube video player" width="480" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Wjxi0snEu98" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><a href="http://app.ccsa.org/apps/mapapp/map.aspx?Zip=&amp;Distance=10&amp;County=">Find more Oakland charter schools.</a></p>\n', 'Get to know Oakland\'s charter schools', 'Get to know some of the amazing and diverse charter schools in Oakland and the Bay Area, including Oakland Charter Academy (2009 California Charter School of the Year), Aspire Public Schools, KIPP and Envision.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '26-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 26, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/26-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(772, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p>Muchas families elijen las escuelas chárter porque están buscando mejores opciones educativas y no están satisfechos con el estatus quo. Las escuelas chárter ofrecen una gran variedad de ambientes de aprendizaje.  Algunas tienen currículos especializados; otras se enfocan en lo más básico y esencial.  Algunas escuelas chárter son muy similares a escuelas públicas convenciales, mientras que otras ofrecen cursos por computadora y no tienen un lugar físico donde reunirse.  Lo que las chárter si tienen en común es que son lugares en los cuales se fomenta y se aprecia la participación de los padres de familia, y los maestros tienen la flexibilidad de hacer lo que consideren una prioridad-- enseñar.  Y, siendo escuelas públicas, toda escuela chárter está abierta al público en general, y son gratuitas.</p>\n\n<h2>Identifique las prioridades educativas de su familia</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>¿Cuál es el estilo de aprendizaje de su hijo/a?</li>\n<li>¿Se desenvuelve mejor en grupos pequeños?</li>\n<li>¿Tiene su hijo/a interés por las artes?</li>\n<li>¿Estaría su hijo/a más a gusto en una escuela de estudio independiente?\nEstas son sólo algunas de las opciones disponibles en las escuelas chárter.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Antes de Tomar Una Decisión</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Conozca más sobre la escuela de su interés, leyendo toda información disponible.</li>\n<li>Visite la escuela, y hable con los maestros.</li>\n<li>Observe como los maestros interactúan con sus estudiantes.</li>\n<li>Averigüe cuál es el número de estudiantes por cada maestro.</li>\n<li>Si tiene una pregunta, no dude en hacerla; no tenga miedo o pena.</li>\n<li>Una de las mejores maneras de buscar información sobre cualquier escuela es hablando con otros padres de familia--por ejemplo, pregunte si les gusta la escuela, o si los maestros son buenos.\nLas escuelas chárter, por mayoría, piden la participación de padres de familia.  Pregunte sobre oportunidades de trabajo voluntario en la escuela.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2010/10/que-es-una-escuela-charter.html">Hoja de Datos: ¿Qué es una escuela chárter?</a>\n<a href="/2010/12/charter-schools-public-school-reinvented---spanish-version.html">Lea más sobre las ventajas de las escuelas chárter.</a></li>\n</ul>\n', 'Cómo Escoger la Mejor Escuela Para Su Hijo', 'Muchas families elijen las escuelas chárter porque están buscando mejores opciones educativas y no están satisfechos con el estatus quo. Hay mucho para considerar cuando usted está buscando la escuela mejor para su hijo.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '25-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 25, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/25-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(773, 3, '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '<p><img alt="kid-at-desk.jpg" src="/images/kid-at-desk.jpg" width="250" height="375" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" />\nMany parents and students choose charter schools because they are seeking a better education and they are dissatisfied with the status quo of traditional education. Charter schools offer a wide variety of learning environments. Some have a theme or specialized curriculum; others focus on fundamentals. Some charter schools look like traditional public schools; others offer online classes and may not even have a physical campus. What all charters have in common is that they are places where meaningful parental involvement is encouraged and valued, and teachers are free to do what they do best - teach. And as public schools, every charter school is open to the entire community and tuition-free.\nHere are some key questions to ask when you\'re choosing a school.</p>\n\n<h2>Identify your family\'s educational priorities</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What is your child\'s learning style?</li>\n<li>Does he/she do best in small groups?</li>\n<li>Does your child have an interest in the arts?</li>\n<li>Would he/she benefit from an independent study school?\nThese are just some of the options available at charters.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Making the Decision</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Do research by reading school information.</li>\n<li>Visit the school and talk to teachers.</li>\n<li>Watch the teachers in action with students.</li>\n<li>Pay attention to the student-to-teacher ratio.</li>\n<li>Always feel free to ask questions</li>\n<li>One of the best ways to learn about a school is to ask other parents - How do they feel about the School? Are the teachers effective?\nFinally, a majority of charter schools ask parents to be involved in the school community. Inquire about volunteer hours and opportunities at the school.\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2010/09/fact-sheet-for-parents-about-charter-schools.html">Get a fact sheet about charter schools.</a>\n<a href="/2010/12/charter-schools-public-school-reinvented.html">Read about some of the advantages of charter schools.</a></li>\n</ul>\n', 'How to choose the right school for your child', 'Many parents and students choose charter schools because they are seeking a better education and they are dissatisfied with the status quo of traditional education. Use this guide to find the school that is the best fit for your child.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '24-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '2016-01-13 04:14:45', '', 24, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/24-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
