(797, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p>You\'re invited to the 3rd Annual Charter School Parent Summit which will be held Wednesday, February 29, 2012. Charter school parents from throughout California will gather to learn about parent organizing and to strategize about the future of the charter school movement.\n<a href="/_DSC0259.JPG"><img alt="Parent Summit 2011 Two moms snapshot" src="/assets_c/2012/02/_DSC0259-thumb-500x332-2373.jpg" width="500" height="332" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a>\nHighlights:\n- Sacramento Mayor Kevin Johnson will speak at the morning general session about why he feels so passionately about improving our schools that he helped found a charter school.\n- Assemblymember Holly Mitchell will join parents for the morning meet and greet.\n- Workshops will cover everything grassroots organizing to getting your voice online.\n- The day will close out with parents participating in the Funding Equity Rally on the capitol steps!\nThe Summit is free to parent attendees! <a href="http://charterconference.org/2012/registration/parent_summit.php">See more details and register now! </a></p>\n', 'Join us for the 3rd Annual Parent Summit!', 'You\'re invited to the 3rd Annual Charter School Parent Summit which will be held Wednesday, February 29, 2012. Charter school parents from throughout California will gather to learn about parent organizing and to strategize about the future of the charter school movement. Register today! It\'s free!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '58-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 58, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/58-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(798, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p>Futuro College Prep charter elementary school opened in the fall of 2010. Together with its sister school, Endeavor College Prep charter middle school, the two schools serve over 450 children from the neighborhoods of Boyle Heights, Lincoln Heights, El Sereno, and East L.A. Both schools are committed to providing an education for students that will prepare them for a future of choice and opportunity and have had a great response from parents who are excited about the college prep curriculum they offer.\nTheir biggest challenge? Obtaining a single facility in the Boyle Heights community, where their charters were originally approved.\nUnlike traditional schools, charter schools aren\'t automatically provided a facility. Under the state law Proposition 39, school districts are required to provide charter schools with facilities that are "reasonably equivalent" to those used by non-charter students within the district. However, for the past three years, the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) has failed to provide Futuro Prep and Endeavor College Prep a contiguous space located in the community of Boyle Heights, where most of their families live. For the 2011-12 school year, LAUSD offered Endeavor a split campus agreement, which divided the school across two sites. As the schools grow each year, it is uncertain which location(s) the District will designate.  Currently, some parents have to drop off their students at two different places.\n<a href="/futuro_prep.jpg"><img alt="Futuro Prep Facilities Map" src="/assets_c/2012/02/futuro_prep-thumb-530x345-2333.jpg" width="530" height="345" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a>\nThis year, Futuro Prep is at one site, but it is more than five miles away from where most of its families reside. The school is expanding to third grade next year and parents are concerned that they won\'t have enough space at their current site and may be split among two campuses. Futuro Prep parents recently sent letters to the LAUSD school board, asking for their support in securing a facility in the Boyle Heights community.\n- Learn more about this issue with our "<a href="/2011/06/a-parents-guide-to-charter-facility-challenges.html">Parent\'s Guide to Charter School Facilities Challenges</a>."\n- Learn more about <a href="http://www.endeavorcollegeprep.org/">Endeavor College Prep</a> and <a href="http://www.futuroprep.org/">Futuro Prep</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>In Their Own Words</h2>\n\n<p><em>Education is really important for my family. That\'s why we\'ve decided to put our daughter in a school with high academic performance, discipline and respect. That\'s why I take her to Futuro Prep charter school - because the neighborhood school to which she is assigned isn\'t very good. I\'ve seen a significant change in my daughter - both academically and emotionally. It doesn\'t matter that we have to push ourselves a bit to take her to Futuro Prep, driving 9 miles and getting up at 5:30 am every day. I believe this effort is well worth it for the future of my daughter.</em>\n- <strong>Guillermina Lara</strong>\n<em>Futuro Prep has done so much for my son. They have taught him and I have seen the difference and how much he has learned. We live in East LA, 15-20 minutes away by car from the school but it doesn\'t matter how long it takes. What matters is my son likes the school, his teachers and the way they teach.</em>\n- <strong>Lucia Baez</strong>\n<em>I am sending my child to Futuro Prep because I feel that he is getting a better education rather than sending him to one of the surrounding district schools. I have researched the school rankings in the Los Angeles area and was devastated by the low scores. I really appreciated the fact that Futuro Prep offered two teachers in kindergarten. I see the difference in my son from just one year at this school.</em>\n- <strong>Jenny Vu and Andrew Carbajal</strong>\n<em>I am very pleased with the way the school has improved my daughters academically...It worries me that there will not be any space for the school to be together next year. I believe the school\'s test scores show improvement and therefore merit their own school.</em>\n- <strong>Irene Garcia</strong></p>\n', 'Help us find a home for our school!', 'Futuro Prep Charter School in Los Angeles has a great academic program and passionate parents, but what they don\'t have is a permanent home for their school. Parents are reaching out to the LA school board for help.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '57-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 57, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/57-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(799, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p>¿Qué es una escuela chárter? Aprenda más con nuestro nuevo video sobre esta clase de escuelas públicas.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/t99qKgV5LoQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Video: Charters 101', '¿Qué es una escuela chárter? Aprenda más con nuestro nuevo video sobre esta clase de escuelas públicas.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '56-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 56, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/56-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(800, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p><a href="/parent_leader_meeting_1-18-11.jpg"><img alt="parent_leader_meeting_2-18-11.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/parent_leader_meeting_1-18-11-thumb-530x316-2273.jpg" width="530" height="316" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a>\nOn Feb. 18, Families That Can hosted its first regional meeting specifically for Parent School Site Leaders with representatives from a dozen Los Angeles charter schools. FTC plans to offer these meetings on a quarterly basis to give parent leaders a chance to share best practices, access useful parent resources and get ideas for engaging their parents.\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.267612463304880.65430.102530249813103&amp;type=1">Check out photos from the first meeting!</a>\nWe recognize that a vital component of a school\'s success is due to the level of parent involvement, and despite cuts to education, we want to ensure that parent engagement will not be affected. Parent leaders were able to share best practices, learn new ideas to increase their parent involvement, and hear about all the resources that Families That Can provides. A highlight of the this conversation was having Watts Learning Center invite Alliance College Ready Schools to provide some of their parent leadership workshops at their sites! This is exactly the kind of collaboration we hope to promote.\nWith Schools We Can Believe In Rally fast approaching on February 4, we were able to provide our Parent Leaders with up-to-date information as well as walk them through our online resource toolkit at <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/rallytoolkit">www.ccsa.org/rallytoolkit</a>.  We shared that we currently have a commitment of 6,200 supporters that will be attending this Rally, an astonishing number! The immediate reaction from the Parent Leaders was..."How do we keep this momentum going?"\nFamilies That Can is taking this momentum to the State Capitol! They were able to hear about our 3rd annual parent summit that will be held on February 29th, where our Parent Leaders will be receiving professional development and will also be empowered to voice their support for their GREAT public charter school at our rally on the lawn of the state capitol.\nAll our Parent Leaders left excited for the all opportunities and resources to come from Families That Can!\nSchool represented at the first meeting were:\n- Futuro College Prep\n- Camino Nuevo\n- Watts Learning Center\n- Synergy Academy\n- Alliance\n- Valor Academy\n- Global Education Academy\n- ICEF Public Schools\n- Culture and Language Academy of Success - CLAS\nPlease keep an eye out open for our 2nd Los Angeles Region Parent Leadership Meeting that will be held in April 2012. More details to come!</p>\n', 'Families That Can hosts its first meeting for Parent Leaders/Coordinators', 'On Feb. 18, Families That Can hosted its first regional meeting specifically for Parent School Site Leaders with representatives from a dozen Los Angeles charter schools. FTC plans to offer these meetings on a quarterly basis to give parent leaders a chance to share best practices, access useful parent resources and get ideas for engaging their parents.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '55-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 55, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/55-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(801, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p><em>At our <a href="/2012/01/join-us-feb-4.html">citywide rally</a> on Feb. 4, we will ask our elected leaders to sign this pledge.</em>\nLos Angeles is one of the greatest cities in the world.  The parents of Los Angeles deserve public schools that match the greatness of our city.  As a leader of this city, I commit to do all that I can to give the children of Los Angeles more schools that are highly effective and to elevate the importance of parental engagement to ensure we once again have Schools We Can Believe In!\nTo the parents of the Los Angeles Unified School District, I____________________________________, pledge to:\n1.  Defend your right to choose the best public educational opportunity for your child; and\n2.  Enable you to be educated on all of the options available to you within our public school system; and\n3.  Support your right to hold all public schools accountable for educating your child at a high level; and\n4.  Protect your right to have your child\'s education funded at a fair and equitable level; and\n5.  Affirm your right to have access to safe, equitable, public school facilities for your child; and\n6.  Safeguard your right to demand that every high quality school, including public charter schools, are provided all of the support, resources and funding necessary to operate, continue to operate and expand to serve the children of Los Angeles.\n7.  Advocate for public education funding levels that demonstrate that the children of California are a state priority.</p>\n', '"Schools We Can Believe In" Elected Leaders Pledge', '*At our [citywide rally](/2012/01/join-us-feb-4.html) on Feb. 4, we will ask our elected leaders to sign on to this pledge.*\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '54-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 54, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/54-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(802, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '<p>Muchos estudiantes en Los Angeles no están recibiendo la educación que realmente se merecen. Los estudiantes merecen mejores escuelas, y los padres merecen saber cuál es el rendimiento de las escuelas de sus hijos y cuáles son sus opciones educativas.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/v-XJRouXVEg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Por eso, más que 5,000 padres de familia, maestros y estudiantes se unieron el 4 de febrero 2012 en frente del coliseo de Los Ángeles para levantar la voz.\nExigimos por todos los estudiantes que asisten a escuelas públicas para que tengan:\n- ¡Escuelas de Alta Calidad en Cada Comunidad!\n- ¡Edificios Escolares de Alta Calidad!\n- ¡El Mismo Financiamiento!\n- ¡Que La Voz de Cada Padre Sea Escuchada!\nLos oradores en el evento fueron:\n- Antonio Villaraigosa, Alcalde de Los Ángeles\n- Mónica García, Presidenta de la Junta Directiva del LAUSD\n- Dr. John Deasy, Superintendente del LAUSD\n- Ana Ponce, Fundadora, Camino Nuevo Charter Academies\n- Yolie Flores, Directora Ejecutiva de Communities for Teaching Excellence\n- Corri Ravare, Directora Ejecutiva de Families That Can\nGabriela Teissier de Univisión 34 fue la maestra de ceremonias.\n<strong>Nuestras Organizaciones Socias</strong>\nTrabajamos con varios grupo comunitarios que quieren mejorar la educación pública en Los Angeles para realizar el evento y involucrar a aun más padres en este trabajo. ¡Haga clic en sus logos para aprender más!</p>\n\n<table width="530" border="0">\n<td><a href="http://www.afabc.org/"><img alt="afabclogo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/afabclogo-thumb-150x59-2270.jpg" width="150" height="59" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.dfer.org/branches/california/"><img alt="dfer_logo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/dfer_logo-thumb-150x113-2283.jpg" width="150" height="113" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://4teachingexcellence.org/"><img alt="communities4te.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/communities4te-thumb-150x117-2268.jpg" width="150" height="117" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a href="http://www.familiesinschools.org/"><img alt="families_in_schools_logo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/FIS Purple Logo HI-thumb-150x63-2282.jpg" width="150" height="63" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.unitedwayla.org/"><img alt="unitedway.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/unitedway-thumb-150x63-2290.jpg" width="150" height="63" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.edvoice.org/"><img alt="edvoice_logo.jpg" src="/edvoice%20logo%20CMYK%20Color%20copy.jpg" width="73" height="41" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>La manifestación fue el inicio de una serie de eventos y acciones durante todo el año que viene. ¡Inscríbase para mantenerse al tanto y recibir invitaciones a todos los eventos!</p>\n', '5,000 + Padres de Familia Se Unen Para Exigir Mejores Escuelas', 'Los padres se unen el 4 de febrero para exigir buenas escuelas en cada comunidad.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '52-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '2016-01-13 04:18:18', '', 52, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/52-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(803, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>Way too many students in Los Angeles aren\'t getting the education they deserve. Students deserve better schools and parents deserve to know how their children\'s schools are doing and what their options are. That\'s why more than 5,000 parents from across LA came out on a Saturday morning to stand up and speak out. Thanks to all of you, it was truly an incredible kick-off to our campaign to make sure our elected leaders put public education front and center.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="530" height="299" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/v-XJRouXVEg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Parents stood up on Feb. 4, 2012 to demand:\n- High-quality schools in every neighborhood for all public school students!\n- Quality space to learn for all public school students!\n- Equal funding for all public school students!\n- That parent voices are heard!\nAt the rally, we asked our elected representatives to sign on to the <a href="/2012/01/schools-we-can-believe-in-elected-leaders-pledge.html">"Schools We Can Believe In" Pledge</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>Speakers at the Rally</h2>\n\n<p>We heard from several leaders who are committed to improving public schools, as well as some inspiring educators and parents. Univision Anchor Gabriela Teissier, who is a charter school parent, did an incredible job emceeing our event.\n- Antonio Villaraigosa, Mayor of Los Angeles\n- Corri Ravare, Executive Director of Families That Can\n- Monica Garcia, LAUSD Board President\n- Dr. John Deasy, LAUSD Superintendent\n- Connie Rivera, Parent, Alliance for College Ready Public Schools\n- Ana Ponce, Founder of Camino Nuevo Charter Academies\n- Angelina Saenz, Teacher, Aldama Elementary\n- Yolie Flores, Executive Director of Communities for Teaching Excellence\n- Cindy Rueda, Parent, Community Charter Middle School (PUC Schools)\nMore than 100 different charter schools participated in the event. See a <a href="http://batchgeo.com/map/fb8a1fcb0eebcaf63dbaf7a0d740bb23">map showing all the schools that were there.</a>\n<strong>Our Partners</strong>\nWe worked with many with other local non-profits and community groups that are passionate about improving our public schools to make this rally a success and we will continue to work with them to engage parents on these critical issues. Click on their logos to learn more!</p>\n\n<table width="530" border="0">\n<tr>\n<td><a href="http://www.afabc.org/"><img alt="afabclogo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/afabclogo-thumb-150x59-2270.jpg" width="150" height="59" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.dfer.org/branches/california/"><img alt="dfer_logo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/dfer_logo-thumb-150x113-2283.jpg" width="150" height="113" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://4teachingexcellence.org/"><img alt="communities4te.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/communities4te-thumb-150x117-2268.jpg" width="150" height="117" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a href="http://www.familiesinschools.org/"><img alt="families_in_schools_logo.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/FIS Purple Logo HI-thumb-150x63-2282.jpg" width="150" height="63" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.unitedwayla.org/"><img alt="unitedway.jpg" src="/assets_c/2012/01/unitedway-thumb-150x63-2290.jpg" width="150" height="63" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a></td>\n<td><a href="http://www.edvoice.org/"><img alt="edvoice_logo.jpg" src="/edvoice%20logo%20CMYK%20Color%20copy.jpg" width="73" height="41" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td><a href="http://parentrevolution.org/"><img alt="parentrevolution_logo.png" src="/assets_c/2012/02/parentrevolution_logo-thumb-150x54-2297.png" width="150" height="54" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0 auto 20px;" /></a>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>What\'s next?</h3>\n\n<p>There are many important elections coming up, including LA Mayor, City Council, and School Board in 2013. Today is the kick-off of a year-long campaign to ensure that improving our public schools is at the top of the agenda for all elected officials and candidates. In the months to come, we\'ll be inviting you to more events and asking you take action and reach out to the elected officials in your area.</p>\n\n<h3>What can you do right now?</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Tell your friends and family!</strong>\nShare your story and tell them why you came  to the rally today and why you support charter public schools.\n<strong>Invite elected representatives to visit your school!</strong>\nNothing has more impact on decision-makers than hearing from parents, students and teachers first-hand. Work with your school principal to plan an event and don\'t forget to invite the community to your campus for National Charter Schools Week, May 6-12, 2012.\nMake sure you get important action alerts and the latest news:\n- Click "Join Us" at the top of the page to sign up for our e-newsletter.\n- Text GOCHARTER to 41411 to get all the latest updates!\n- Like us on <a href="http://www.facebook.com/familiesthatcan">Facebook</a>.\n- Follow us on <a href="http://www.twitter.com/familiesthatcan">Twitter</a>!</p>\n', '5,000+ Parents Rally for "Schools We Can Believe In"', 'On Feb. 4, charter school parents from across Los Angeles rallied at Exposition Park to tell our elected leaders: Put students first!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '51-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 51, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/51-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(804, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>El año pasado, gracias a usted y otros defensores de las escuelas chárter, pudimos detener la AB 1172 (Mendoza), una propuesta de ley que contemplaba poner más obstáculos en la aprobación de nuevas escuelas chárter.  Ahora, la AB 1172 está de vuelta y el Comité de Educación de la Asamblea Estatal planea escucharla el próximo 11 de enero de 2012.\n<a href="http://www.votervoice.net/groups/ftc/advocacy/?issueid=26934">¡Escriba a los miembros del Comité hoy mismo para detener ésta propuesta de ley!</a>\nLa AB 1172 permitiría a los distritos escolares rechazar peticiones de nuevas escuelas chárter si se puede determinar que habría "un impacto fiscal negativo contra el distrito."  Nosotros pensamos que toda petición debe ser evaluada sobre el impacto positivo que una nueva escuela chárter tendría con estudiantes, ¡no en el impacto negativo contra adultos! Los fondos estatales no "pertenecen" ni a las escuelas chárter ni a los distritos; los fondos estatales  pertenecen a los estudiantes que están asistiendo a escuelas públicas.\n¡Levante su voz en defensa de las escuelas chárter de California!</p>\n', 'Alerta de Acción: AB 1172', 'El año pasado, gracias a usted y otros defensores de las escuelas chárter, pudimos detener la AB 1172 (Mendoza), una propuesta de ley que contemplaba poner más obstáculos en la aprobación de nuevas escuelas chárter.  ¡Escriba a los miembros del Comité hoy mismo!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '50-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 50, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/50-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(805, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>Last year, thanks to you and other charter school supporters, we stopped AB 1172 (Mendoza), a bill that would have put up more hurdles to new charters being approved. Now AB 1172 is back and set to be heard by the Assembly Education Committee on Jan. 11, 2012.\n<strong>We need you to <a href="http://www.votervoice.net/core.aspx?APP=GAC&amp;AID=1321&amp;issueid=26930&amp;SiteID=-1">write the committee</a> today to stop this bill!</strong>\nAB 1172 would allow districts to reject a petition for a new charter school based on whether the charter would have "a negative fiscal impact on the district." We say that petitions should be evaluated on whether the new school will have a positive impact for students, not on whether it will have a negative impact on adults! Funding does not "belong" to either a charter school or a district; it belongs to the students that are being educated.\nStand up for California\'s charter schools and make your voice heard!</p>\n', 'Action Alert: Speak Out on AB 1172!', 'We need you to contact the Assembly Education Committee before Jan. 11 to stop a bill that would put up more hurdles to new charters being approved.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 49, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(806, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p><a href="/Rally%20and%20end%20of%20the%20year%20062.JPG"><img alt="Sac High Rally Protesters Dec 2011" src="/assets_c/2012/01/Rally and end of the year 062-thumb-200x150-2243.jpg" width="200" height="150" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></a>In December, the Sacramento City Unified School District (SCUSD) Board dropped a proposal that would have forced 1,100 charter students to move off the Sac High campus to another site more than two miles away through a "campus swap" with West Campus (a district magnet school).\n<strong><a href="http://www.ccsa.org/blog/members/2011/12/sacramento-city-trustees-drop-plans-to-move-sac-high-and-ps7.html">See news coverage.</a></strong></p>\n\n<h2>Parents Mobilize to Speak Out</h2>\n\n<p>When the swap was first proposed in November, Families That Can held a student leadership workshop during lunch at Sac High where students suggested partnering with West Campus students to march in solidarity against the swap.\nThey did just that on Dec. 8 board meeting, over 60 Sac High and West Campus parents, students and teachers marched together to the board meeting. The group was greeted by news cameras and reporters, and many people spoke out during public comment with the message: "Don\'t mess with success!"\n<em>"We will work together. We have to. Our kids need to be here tonight to remind board members who it is they\'re supposed to be serving.  This is wrong and messed up."</em> - Xochitl Pasilla, West Campus parent\n<em>"They\'re doing this because they think they\'ll get away with it because they think no one\'s paying attention.  We\'re paying attention - and this is not OK!"</em> - Gladys Mitchell, St. Hope Parent</p>\n\n<h2>School Board Drops Proposal but It\'s Not Over Yet</h2>\n\n<p>On Dec. 8, the Board of Trustees decided to pull the "swap" from the table and some members even apologized for presenting the "solution" in the first place.\nHowever, this isn\'t the first attack on Sac High and it won\'t be the last. Though the "swap" is off the table, SCUSD Board member Patrick Kennedy says that he would still like to explore how to "best utilize" the Sacramento High School campus, even though the campus is currently home to not only the 900+  high school students, but also the 170+ middle school students that attend St. Hope\'s PS7.</p>\n\n<h2>Sac High IS our neighborhood school</h2>\n\n<p>Up until 2003, Sac High was a traditional district school. It had low test scores and high drop-out rates when it was converted into Sacramento Charter High School, operated under St. Hope Public Schools. Test scores have increased, but more importantly, more students are graduating and attending 4-year universities at higher rates than ever before.\nBut still Boardmember Kennedy claims that his "community" (still unidentified) wants a comprehensive high school in Oak Park.  Parents and students encouraged him to consider Sac High to be that "comprehensive neighborhood" high school - with the strong school spirit (and tradition), a nice facility, performing arts and strong athletics and academics.\nOne student asked the board member, "Sac High doesn\'t close its doors to any student, so why can\'t this be the \'neighborhood\' school?  We are a public school."\nAnother concerned St. Hope supporter asked Kennedy, "If you\'re not going to publicly support Sac High, who else is responsible for protecting these babies?"\nSt. Hope has plans to continue engaging their school community into 2012.  Board member Kennedy has agreed to return to Sac High to answer many unanswered questions and continue dialogue with the real community affected - St. Hope parents, students, teachers, and supporters.\nThis experience has shown us how important it is to be united to stand up for our students and our schools.</p>\n', 'Parents Succeed in Preserving Sac High', 'In December, the Sacramento City Unified School District (SCUSD) Board dropped a proposal that would have forced 1,100 charter students to move off the Sac High campus to another site more than two miles away thanks to the efforts of parents who mobilized and spoke out.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '53-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 53, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/53-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(807, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>What is a charter school and what sets these independent public schools apart from other schools? Find out everything you need to know in this short video!</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/EdPFWZOpxdQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Learn more and <a href="http://app.ccsa.org/apps/mapapp/map.aspx?Zip=&amp;Distance=10&amp;County=">find a charter school</a> in your area on the <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/understanding/">California Charter Schools Association web site</a>.</p>\n', 'Charter Schools 101', 'What is a charter school and what sets these independent public schools apart from other schools? Find out everything you need to know in this short video!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '63-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 63, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/63-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(808, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>A new report issued by the California Charter Schools Association found that charter schools are accelerating the achievement of African American students.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/hGmelk57y-o" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>"What this report shows is that African American students are experiencing better outcomes in charters, and that as laboratories of innovation, California\'s highly effective charter public schools can demonstrate proven paths to success that should be replicated nationally," said Dr. Aisha Toney, Director of Research, CCSA.\nAmong the report\'s findings:</p>\n\n<h3>African American parents are choosing charter schools in high numbers.</h3>\n\n<p>African American students make up 6% of students statewide, but 9% of students in charter public schools. In some communities, African Americans are twice as likely to enroll in a charter than a traditional public school.</p>\n\n<h3>Charter schools are helping to close the achievement gap.</h3>\n\n<p>Charter schools serving African American students are realizing better outcomes compared to traditional public schools. While charters make up only 9% of schools statewide, they represent 39% of highly effective schools for African American students.\nThe study also looked at three schools that are doing a phenomenal job of serving African American students.\nGet to know the schools:\n- <a href="/2011/10/watts-learning-center-in-los-angeles.html">Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles</a>\n- <a href="/2011/10/kipp-bridge-in-oakland.html">KIPP Bridge in Oakland</a>\n- <a href="/2011/10/st-hope-public-school-7-in-sacramento.html">PS7 in Sacramento</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/understanding/research/africanamericanreport/">Read the full report.</a>\n<a href="http://www.ccsa.org/2011/10/fact-sheet-chartering-and-choice-as-an-achievement-gap-closing-reform.html">Download a fact sheet to share with others.\n</a></p>\n', 'Charters Accelerate African American Student Achievement', 'A new report issued by the California Charter Schools Association found that charter schools are accelerating the achievement of African American students. Find out more and learn about three charter schools that are doing an exceptional job.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '48-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 48, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/48-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(809, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>St. HOPE Public School 7 (PS7) is a K-8 charter school located in Sacramento. It was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. <a href="http://youtu.be/hGmelk57y-o">See a video about the report</a>.\n"If you are a parent in Sacramento county, charter schools are your northern star," said Margaret Fortune, founder of Fortune Schools. "If you are a parent that is making the decision, it is your choice. It is about your children and following what is best for them, even if it takes courage."\n"We believe that black and Latino kids have to have an opportunity to succeed and achieve the American dream. If you look at the achievement gap in Sacramento, there is an 151 point gap between black kids and white kids. Over the last eight years, that gap has closed five points. At that rate, it will take 258 years to close the achievement gap. I don\'t know about you, but I\'m not waiting that long," said Sacramento Mayor Kevin Johnson, one of the founders of PS7.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/15531078?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0" width="559" height="317" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><a href="http://vimeo.com/15531078">PS7 Featured On KCRA</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/user4883473">PS7</a> on <a href="http://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.ps7.org/">Learn more about PS7</a>.</li>\n<li>Hear a parent\'s perspective: <a href="/2011/10/marie-cole-ps7-in-sacramento.html">Marie Cole, PS7</a>\nAre you a parent or student at PS7? We want to hear from you! Why did you choose to go to PS7? What do you like about your school? Send your story to (contact@familiesthatcan.org)[contact@familiesthatcan.org].</li>\n</ul>\n', 'St. HOPE Public School 7 in Sacramento', 'St. HOPE Public School 7 (PS7) is a K-8 charter school located in Sacramento. It was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '47-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 47, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/47-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(810, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>Charter school parent Marie Cole shared her story and perspective at a press conference in September on how charter schools are effectively serving African American students. She is a parent at at PS7 in Sacramento.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/M8lKHaieb2c" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><em>See Marie at minute 27 of the press conference.</em>\nMy oldest son is a senior at Sac High this year. He was in the first fourth-grade class of PS7 when Mayor Kevin Johnson first founded the school. I found the school on a fluke. It was in the summertime and there were yard signs out that said "Charter school opening - enroll your student." I went and met the administrators and signed up. Two weeks later, I got a letter that my son had been accepted.\nI had been lead to believe that my son had a learning disability because, in the second and third grade, he would finish his work more quickly than the other kids, then he would get distracted and he would distract his classmates. His teachers didn\'t have time to give him extra work. We went to PS7 and my son excelled - he was an overachiever and it was a blessing. It wasn\'t something that was frowned upon. It wasn\'t punished - he was encouraged more and more to excel.\nIt made me look at not only wanting to help the school, but to be more a part of his education. At many traditional public schools, you\'re not really allowed to just walk in and say, "Hi, can I help?" They will say, "No, we have a PTA for that." But not here at PS7 - it\'s an open door policy. They want you to come in and be here and volunteer. I kind of became a fixture at the school, which was a blessing. This school is very family-oriented. To see these scores, it\'s awesome. As a parent, it\'s exciting because my son is a part of this.\nFind out more about the African American student report and schools in Oakland and Los Angeles that were also highlighted for being highly effective.</p>\n', 'Marie Cole, PS7 in Sacramento', '"This school is very family-oriented. To see these test scores, it\'s awesome. As a parent, it\'s exciting because my son is a part of this. "\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '46-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 46, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/46-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(811, 3, '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '<p>Watts Learning Center, an elementary charter school in South Los Angeles, was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students. It was also honored as Charter School of the Year in 2007. <a href="http://youtu.be/hGmelk57y-o">See a video about the report</a>.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="410" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/C-awbRJN3to" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>Are you a parent or student at Watts Learning Center? We want to hear from you! Why did you choose to go to a charter school? What do you like about your school? Send your story to <a href="mailto:contact@familiesthatcan.org">contact@familiesthatcan.org</a>.</p>\n', 'Eye on Success: Watts Learning Center in Los Angeles', 'Watts Learning Center, an elementary charter school in South Los Angeles, was recently highlighted in a report by the California Charter Schools Association that looked at schools that are highly effective in educating African American students.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '2016-01-13 04:18:19', '', 45, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(812, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:48', '2016-01-13 04:19:48', '<p>Ayúdenos a difundir información mediante la inclusión de nuestras noticias en su boletín escolar o en su página web. Nosotros incluiremos un breve artículo en este boletín todos los meses para hacer este proceso mucho más fácil para usted.</p>\n\n<h3>¡Victoria para los padres! - LAUSD rechaza resolución que limitaría opciones para padres</h3>\n\n<p>En septiembre, Steve Zimmer, un miembro de la junta directiva del distrito escolar de Los Angeles (LAUSD) propuso una resolución que limitaría la elección de los padres al no permitir que ningunas nuevas escuelas chárter pudieran abrir.\nLos padres hablaron con una sola voz en contra de esta resolucion. Cientos de padres fueron a las juntas de LAUSD, llamaron a los miembros de la junta y se los enviaron cartas. 2,000+ padres firmaron una peticion en contra de la resolution.\nEn el dia del voto, el 13 de noviembre, ¡más de 1.500 padres se manifestaron en frente de la sala de juntas del LAUSD!\nLos padres levantaron sus voces ¡nuestros representantes electos nos oyeron! Los miembros de la junta del LAUSD votaron en contra de esta mala resolución 4-2. La Presidenta de la Junta Mónica García y Miembro de la Junta Tamar Galatzan hablaron a los padres en nuestra manifestación afuera de la sala de juntas, afirmando su apoyo para la elección de los padres y las escuelas chárter de alta calidad. Ambas votaron en contra de la resolución, al igual que Nury Martínez y Richard Vladovic. Sólo Steve Zimmer y Bennett Kayser votaron a favor; Marguerite LaMotte salió de la sala durante la votación.</p>\n\n<h3>¿Qué es el próximo paso?</h3>\n\n<p>Todos los días, nuestros representantes electos toman decisiones importantes que afectan a nuestras escuelas y nuestros hijos. En marzo, tendremos la oportunidad de decidir no sólo quién va a estar a cargo de nuestra ciudad como alcalde/alcaldesa, pero ¿quién nos va a representar en la junta directiva del distrito escolar? Tres asientos serán abiertos para la elección.\nEn los próximos meses, Families That Can se llevará a cabo talleres y eventos como foros de educación de los votantes con los candidatos para educar, capacitar y movilizar a los padres de las escuelas chárter. Contáctenos en contact@familiesthatcan.org si usted o un grupo de padres de su escuela están interesados en organizar una recepción or evento con los candidatos y miembros para la junta directiva del distrito escolar. Diles a todos los padres de su escuela inscribirse para recibir nuestro boletín electrónico gratuito y alertas de acción en www.familiesthatcan.org/inscribase para que no se pierda nada!</p>\n', 'Noticias para Diciembre: ¡Victoria para los padres! - LAUSD rechaza resolución que limitaría opciones para padres', 'Noticias para su boletín informativo para padres - Noticia especial sobre la manifestacion en Los Angeles el 13 de noviembre\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '183-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:48', '2016-01-13 04:19:48', '', 183, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/183-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
