(830, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) is launching a Start-Up Circle in the Bay Area! You are invited to join other educators, parents, and community leaders to learn more about the process of starting a charter school and to discuss the landscape throughout the Bay Area - existing schools, demand for new schools, and more.\nYou\'ll have the opportunity to share ideas, talk with the inspiring founders of <a href="http://www.vincentacademy.org/">Vincent Academy</a> -- Jean Driscoll (Board President, Vincent Academy) and Kate Nichol (Head of School, Vincent Academy), learn about supports available to teams interested in starting a school, and connect with others who also want to see more high-quality schools in the Bay Area.\nThis event will be held on November 8 at 6:30 p.m. at the Oakland School for the Arts, 530 18th Street, Room 315, Oakland. <a href="http://www.meetup.com/startupcircle/events/83338242/">Please RSVP on Meet-up!</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/H3oCQToUT1Q?list=PL5475BDBA283F57CC&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Nov. 8: You\'re invited to Start-up Circle in the Bay Area', 'Have you ever wondered about how to start a charter school? Or how to bring a great new charter school to your neighborhood? Don\'t miss this great event in Oakland!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '164-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '2016-01-13 04:19:50', '', 164, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/164-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(831, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '<p>The California Charter Schools Association (CCSA) is launching a Start-Up Circle! You are invited to join other educators, parents, and community leaders to discuss the process of starting a charter school and the landscape throughout Sacramento County - existing schools, demand for new schools, and more.\nYou\'ll have the opportunity to share ideas, talk with Penny Schwinn (Founder &amp; Head of School, Capitol Collegiate Academy, and Trustee, Sacramento County Board of Education), learn about supports available to teams interested in starting a school, and connect with others who also want to see more high-quality schools in Sacramento County.\nThe first event will be held on October 24 at 6:30 p.m. at the Teach For America Sacramento Offices, 3400 3rd Avenue, Sacramento. <a href="/Start-Up_Circle_Sacramento_10-24-12.pdf">Download a printable flyer.</a>\nPlease feel free to share this information with others and <a href="www.meetup.com/startupcircle">don\'t forget to RSVP here</a>!\nCan\'t make it? <a href="http://www.ccsa.org/starting/">Learn more about how to start a charter school!</a></p>\n', 'Oct. 24: You\'re invited to Start-up Circle in Sacramento', 'Have you ever wondered about how to start a charter school? Or how to bring a great new charter school to your neighborhood? Don\'t miss this great event!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '163-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 163, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/163-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(832, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '<div class="figure embedded-image right"><img alt="saul_guzman_olga_mohan_parent_la.JPG" src="/saul_guzman_olga_mohan_parent_la.JPG" width="320" height="240" class="mt-image-right" style="float: right; margin: 0 0 20px 20px;" /></div>\n\n<p>Recently, <a href="/2012/09/action-alert-la-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-to-stop-charter-schools-and-take-away-parent-choice.html">Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) Board Member Steve Zimmer made a proposal to limit the growth of charter schools in LA</a>. I\'d like to share my story and ask the LAUSD board to listen to the parents and vote no on this resolution.\nMy name is Saul Guzman and I\'m a proud parent at Dr. Olga Mohan Charter High School in Downtown Los Angeles CA, a charter public school where my son is now a 9th grader. I had my son at a private school in Los Angeles for eight years, and he wanted to continue to study at a private high school because of the horrible stories he heard about public schools.  People said that public schools are full of gangsters, they do drugs, the students do not respect their teachers, etc. I was not sure what to do because I wanted the best for my son, so I applied for two well-known private high schools in the Los Angeles area and my son was accepted, but to my surprise, they were so expensive that I could not afford them.  For this reason, I researched on the internet for the best public high school possible. I found Dr. Olga Mohan as the best possibility and was lucky enough that they accepted my son just in time for the school year.\nI have volunteered since the first day of class for pedestrian and traffic control. During this time, I noticed how the whole staff was involved with the students, the teachers have a great rapport with them, the teachers are very respectful, professional and very accommodating, Also the students are very respectful and conduct themselves in a professional manner.\nThis school also has high academic expectations. When my son was at private school, I remember, they were coached only twice in a quarter and it was totally up to the parents\' and students\' choice whether to pass or fail a subject. At Dr. Olga\'s school, the student counselors get very involved with not only the kids but with their parents toward the success of the student. At Dr. Olga School they provide support classes, mandatory tutoring after school, they provide all the necessary tools for the student not to be left behind.  At Dr. Olga Mohan School, the slogan "No kid is left behind" is a true statement.\nThis is my first year as a parent at a public school, but I\'m very impressed with the hard work and dedication from the personnel at Dr. Olga Charter High School.\nFrom the many conversations that I had with parents and teachers at Dr. Olga\'s Charter school, they are very excited as well about sharing the success they\'ve found at this school, 100% of seniors graduated from this school last year, attended college this year.  The school had earned academic awards since first year when opened and parents are even more excited about the great work ahead as Dr. Olga Mohan continues to grow.\n- <a href="/2012/09/action-alert-la-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-to-stop-charter-schools-and-take-away-parent-choice.html">Take action here to tell the LAUSD board to vote against this resolution!</a>\n<em>Saul Guzman is a parent at Dr. Olga Mohan Charter School, which was the 2011 Charter School of the Year.</em></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/s6JY1fbHwlU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Parent Voice: Saul Guzman: "I wanted the best for my son"', '"I wanted the best for my son," says Los Angeles parent Saul Guzman, who recently spoke out against a proposal to stop all charter school growth in LA and shares his personal experiences.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '161-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 161, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/161-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(833, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '<p>Oakland families are invited to join us for this free and fun community event.</p>\n\n<h3>20th Anniversary of Oakland Charter Schools</h3>\n\n<p>*From Military to Montessori, Arts to Science - 20 years of Providing High-quality, Public School Options to Families *\nOur schools\' success is our students\' success and we are so proud of what Oakland charter school students have accomplished. Twenty years after the first charter school opened, Oakland\'s 40 charter schools serve about a quarter of students, providing diverse, high-quality options to families. Join parents, students and educators as together we celebrate, rally and keep up the momentum for the next generation of students.</p>\n\n<h4>Date</h4>\n\n<p>Saturday, Oct. 13, 2012\n8 a.m. - Registration open\n9 a.m. - Celebratory Program Featuring:\n- Noel Gallo, Oakland Unified School District Board Member\n- Jorge Lopez, Executive Director of the Oakland Charter Academy (formerly Jingle Town Charter School), Oakland\'s first charter school\n- Parris Moore, musician and alumna of Oakland School for the Arts\n- Poet Chinaka Hodge and entertainment from The Getback band!\n10 a.m. - noon - Charter School Expo\nAll attendees will need to be registered and checked-in prior to entering the event, so make sure you leave enough time. The program will begin promptly at 9 a.m.</p>\n\n<h4>Location</h4>\n\n<p>Preservation Park\n1233 Preservation Park Way, Oakland, CA 94612\nThe event hall is located on Martin Luther King, Jr. Way between 12th and 14th Streets and three blocks from 12th Street/Oakland City Center BART. Free parking will be available.</p>\n\n<h3>Looking for a school?</h3>\n\n<p>Are you looking to learn more about local charter public schools? Looking for a new elementary, middle or high school that will better suit your child\'s learning needs and desires?\nCome learn more about our individual schools during our charter school expo! School representatives will be able to answer questions about their unique school programs, the history of the school and how to enroll.\nLatonya Hamilton, a parent at Vincent Academy, shares her tips for parents who are looking for a school!</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/ZYuMJbBwHgc?list=PLB96B633C42AA99E3&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Join us Oct. 13  in Oakland for the 20th Anniversary Celebration and Charter School Expo', 'Are you looking for a school for your children? Don\'t miss this chance to learn more about Oakland\'s diverse and extraordinary charter schools!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '159-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 159, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/159-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(834, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '<p>Before you vote on November 6, you have the opportunity to get more information about local candidates running for school board in the Natomas Unified and San Juan Unified School Districts. With so much attention paid to the Presidential Election, it can be hard to get quality information about local races, but Families That Can is here to help. Come to a local voter forum and hear directly from candidates. Learn their views on education and take the opportunity to ask them questions. Cast your ballot with confidence, knowing you made an informed decision.</p>\n\n<h2>Upcoming Candidate Forums</h2>\n\n<h3>Natomas Unified</h3>\n\n<h4>Oct.3</h4>\n\n<p>6 - 8 p.m.\nHosted by the Natomas Community Association\nNatomas High School library\n3301 Fong Ranch Road, Sacramento, CA</p>\n\n<h4>Oct 17</h4>\n\n<p>6:30 - 8pm\nHosted by NP3 students\nNatomas Pacific Pathways Preparatory High School Library\n3700 Del Paso Rd | Sacramento, CA 95834</p>\n\n<h4>Oct.22</h4>\n\n<p>6 - 7:30 p.m.\nHosted by Natomas Charter School students\nBenvenuti Performing Arts Center\n4600 Blackrock Drive| Sacramento, CA</p>\n\n<h3>San Juan Unified</h3>\n\n<h4>Oct. 16</h4>\n\n<p>7 - 8:30 p.m.\nHosted by Families That Can\nCalifornia Montessori Project-Carmichael\n5330 A Gibbons Drive | Carmichael, CA 95608</p>\n\n<h2>Don\'t forget to check out our voter guides!</h2>\n\n<p>Families That Can put together <a href="/2012/09/non-partisan-voter-guides-for-november-6-2012-school-board-elections.html">these non-partisan voter guides for you to learn more about the candidates.</a></p>\n', 'Meet the Sacramento Area School Board Candidates this October', 'Before you vote on November 6, learn more about candidates running for school board in the Natomas Unified and San Juan Unified School Districts. Join us!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '158-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 158, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/158-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(835, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '<p>LATEST UPDATE: In September, Los Angeles Unified School District Board Member Steve Zimmer proposed a resolution to limit parent choice by not allowing any new charter schools to open. Parents <a href="/2012/09/parents-show-in-force-at-the-lausd-board-room-to-fight-for-choice-and-charters.html">rallied in force on Sept. 11</a> and when we came out again on Oct. 9, Boardmember Zimmer responded by postponing the vote to Nov. 13.\nThe pressure from parents is paying off! BUT we can\'t let up!  <strong>Steve Zimmer must continue to hear from us until this resolution is gone for good.</strong></p>\n\n<h3>Major Parent Rally on Tuesday, Nov. 13!</h3>\n\n<p>On Tuesday, November 13, the LAUSD board will vote on Zimmer\'s resolution. We must and we will come out in force to oppose this resolution. Save the date! The meeting will likely be at noon, with a rally at 11 a.m. Once we have the time of the meeting, we will post the details and send out an email with all the details. Don\'t get our emails and our free monthly newsletter? <a href="/join">Make sure you sign up!</a>\n- Download this printable flyer to spread the word: <a href="/Zimmer_resolution_rally_Nov_13_2012_ENGLISH.pdf">ENGLISH</a> / <a href="/Zimmer_resolution_rally_Nov_13_2012_SPANISH.pdf">SPANISH</a></p>\n\n<h3>Contact your boardmember today!</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Do you think parents know what\'s best for their children?</strong>\n<strong>Do you think families should have a choice of schools?</strong>\nLAUSD Board Member Steve Zimmer doesn\'t think so.\n- He wants to limit parent choice.\n- He wants to make it harder for charter schools to operate.\n- He believes you do not need any more good schools in your community.\n- And he\'s doing all of this behind closed doors without parent and community input.\n- <a href="http://laschoolboard.org/sites/default/files/10-09-12OBpost.pdf">Read the draft resolution.</a>\nCall your board member today and tell them to vote "no" on Steve Zimmer\'s Resolution to End Charter Schools and Limit Parent Choice!\nLAUSD needs to hear from parents!\nSend an email to the LAUSD board members using our easy system. Go to:\n<a href="http://action.familiesthatcan.org/">action.familiesthatcan.org</a>\nCall your board member:\nBoard President Mónica García\n213-241-6180, monica.garcia@lausd.net\nTamar Galatzan\n213-241-6386, tamar.galatzan@lausd.net\nBennett Kayser\n213-241-5555, bennett.kayser@lausd.net\nMarguerite LaMotte\n213-241-6382, marguerite.lamotte@lausd.net\nNury Martinez\n213-241-6388, nury.martinez@lausd.net\nRichard Vladovic\n213-241-6385, richard.vladovic@lausd.net\nSteve Zimmer\n213-241-6387, steve.zimmer@lausd.net</p>\n\n<h3>Circulate a petition!</h3>\n\n<p><a href="/zimmer_resolution_parent_petition.doc">Circulate a petition at your school to collect signatures from parents who can\'t attend the meeting.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Sign the online petition!</h3>\n\n<p>A group of charter school parents posted an online petition that parents can also sign. The petition will be presented to the LAUSD board members!\n- <a href="http://www.ipetitions.com/petition/morecharters/">Sign it here - takes just five minutes.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Spread the word</h3>\n\n<p><strong>Robo-call script</strong>\nENGLISH\nThis is NAME, principal of SCHOOL NAME and I\'m calling you because we need you. On Tuesday, November 13, the Los Angeles school board will vote on a major proposal that would hurt our school and take away choices from parents. Boardmember Steve Zimmer wants to stop us from opening more charter schools and make it harder for our school to operate. Our board member needs to hear from parents. I\'m asking you to please take five minutes right now to call our board member: NAME at NUMBER to tell him/her "Vote no on Steve Zimmer\'s resolution to stop parent choice." Again, that phone number is NUMBER. Thank you for your time!\nSPANISH\nHola...le habla (NOMBRE), director/directora de la escuela (NOMBRE DE ESCUELA), y le llamo para pedirle su ayuda.  En el martes, 13 de noviembre, la Junta Escolar del Distrito de Los Angeles va a votar en una propuesta que--de ser aprobada--perjudicaría a nuestras escuelas, y despojaría a padres de familia como usted de opciones escolares para sus hijos.  Steve Zimmer, uno de los miembros de la Junta Directiva, quiere prevenir que se abran nuevas escuelas chárter, y poner obstáculos para hacer el manejo diario de nuestras escuelas mucho más difícil.  El miembro que nos representa en la Junta Directiva necesita escuchar directamente de los padres sobre cómo esta propuesta nos perjudicaría.  Le pido que tome cinco minutos para llamar ahora mismo a su miembro representante:  NOMBRE y NUMERO, para decirle que "vote en contra de la resolución de Steve Zimmer para despojar a los padres de opciones escolares".  Nuevamente, el número telefónico es (NUMERO). Gracias por su tiempo.</p>\n\n<h3>Bus Information</h3>\n\n<p>These two maps will help you see the lay-out of the rally and where buses can drop off parents.\n- <a href="/Nov_13_event_layout.pdf">Event lay-out</a>\n- <a href="/zimmer_rally_event_map.pdf">Event Map (Updated 11-8-12)</a>\nGiven the limited parking, we recommend that schools use buses:\n- <a href="/Bus_Reimbursement_form.doc">Bus Reimbursement Form</a></p>\n\n<h3>Sign-up Sheets</h3>\n\n<p>Please have all parents who are coming to the rally fill out the sign-up sheets on the bus - the Families That Can team will collect them when the bus arrives. It\'s 100% free to be a part of Families That Can and parents who sign up will receive our free monthly newsletter for charter school parents as well as invites to workshops and events in LA.\nWe\'re provide two options - a grid that can be passed around on clip board or a one page sign-up sheet that each parent can fill out individually.\n- One-page sign-up sheet: <a href="/FTC_join_handout_general.pdf">ENGLISH</a> / <a href="/FTC_join_handout_general_spanish_11-7-12.pdf">SPANISH</a>\n- Sign-up grid (Please note this is legal size - 8.5 x 14"): <a href="/FTC_sign_up_sheet_legal_size.pdf">FTC Sign-up sheet</a></p>\n', 'Action Alert: LA Board Member Steve Zimmer wants to stop charter schools and take away parent choice!', 'Save the date - major parent rally at LAUSD on Nov. 13!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '143-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '2016-01-13 04:19:51', '', 143, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/143-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(836, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Con la Cuenta TripleBoost de EARN, usted recibe $3 por cada $1 que usted ahorre para la educación de su hijo. Puede ahorrar hasta $500 y recibir $1,500 en fondos que da EARN, dándole un total de $2,000 para invertir en la educación de su hijo.\nSu hijo debe estar entre las edades de 10 a 18 años en el momento que usted abra una cuenta.\n- <a href="http://www.earn.org/espanol/espanol_sign_up/cuenta_tripleboost/">¡Conteste 8 preguntas fáciles para ver si usted es elegible para abrir una Cuenta TripleBoost!</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/4kTCOXVuEio?list=PL7426FA758285900D&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<h3>Sobre EARN</h3>\n\n<p>EARN es una organización, reconocida y premiada, sin ánimo de lucro, con base en California que proporciona a los trabajadores de bajos ingresos el poder de crear prosperidad económica para sus familias y para sus futuras generaciones.</p>\n', 'Usted puede recibir $3 por cada $1 que usted ahorre para la educación de su hijo', '¡Conteste 8 preguntas fáciles para ver si usted es elegible para abrir una Cuenta TripleBoost!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '157-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 157, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/157-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(837, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>With the TripleBoost Account, parents of children ages 10-18 receive $3 for every $1 saved for their child\'s education. Parents save $500 and receive $1,500 in match money for a total of $2,000 to invest in their child\'s education. Funds can be used for:\n- College or vocational training\n- Tutoring\n- Summer enrichment camps or after-school programs\n- Music, art, or dance classes\n- A computer,\n- And more!\n<a href="http://www.earn.org/financial_services/info/tripleboost_quiz?/tripleboost">Find out if you\'re eligible!</a></p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/aKDlQ5tG5zo?list=PL7426FA758285900D&amp;hl=en_US" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p><br>\n<br></p>\n\n<h3>About EARN</h3>\n\n<p>Everyone dreams of a better future for their family. For low-wage families, those dreams may be about going to college, buying a first home, starting a business, or having savings to fall back on during tough times.\nBut for millions of Americans, those dreams can seem unreachable. That\'s where EARN comes in. EARN is a nonprofit that gives low-income working families the power to create prosperity for generations. <a href="http://www.earn.org">Learn more.</a></p>\n', 'Parents can receive $3 for every $1 saved for their children\'s education', 'Find out if you\'re eligible and sign up today!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '156-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 156, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/156-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(838, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Rosa Vargas es madre de dos estudiantes en Oakland Charter Academy. Comparte sus experiencias con las escuelas charter.\nRosa Vargas maneja largas distancias cada día para que sus hijos puedan asistir a una escuela chárter. Dice que vale la pena y alenta a los otros padres conocer sus opciones de escuela. Rosa es madre de dos estudiantes en Oakland Charter Academy.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/WegDGC1TZgw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>También aparece en este un video en inglés.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/KmYOeiTaGwM" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Voces de los Padres: "Las escuelas chárter se enfocan más en la educación"', 'Rosa Vargas es madre de dos estudiantes en Oakland Charter Academy. Comparte sus experiencias con las escuelas charter.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '155-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 155, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/155-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(839, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Rosa Vargas, who grew up in Oakland, shares why she chose to send her children to charter schools instead of to Oakland Unified district schools. Her oldest son attended American Indian and two younger children currently attend Oakland Charter Academy.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/KmYOeiTaGwM" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<p>She also recorded a video in Spanish to share with other parents.</p>\n\n<div class="video-container"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/WegDGC1TZgw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n', 'Video: "I didn\'t want my children to be a drop out like me"', 'Rosa Vargas, who grew up in Oakland, shares why she chose to send her children to charter schools instead of to Oakland Unified district schools.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '154-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 154, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/154-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(840, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="voter_guide_promo_pic.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/09/voter_guide_promo_pic-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>FTC has created easy-to-read, nonpartisan voter guides to help you learn more about the candidates running for school board in a variety of communities across the state. Find out where candidates stand on education so that you can make informed decisions when you cast your ballot.\nFTC\'s <a href="/2012/07/families-that-can-launches-the-civics-campaign.html">CIVICS campaign</a> is a statewide, non-partisan effort to encourage voter participation in the upcoming elections. Sometimes voters lack the information they need to make decisions about candidates, especially in local elections. This year, Families That Can asked candidates in a variety of school board races across the state to share their views on education. Their responses were gathered and packaged into our handy nonpartisan voter guides to help educate voters about their choices. "Non-partisan" means these guides were not developed to promote specific candidates or viewpoints. Share these voter guides with your friends and family members so that they can become informed voters, too!\n- <a href="/natomas_voter_guide_9-24-12.pdf">Voter Guide - Natomas Unified School District, Sacramento</a>\n- <a href="/San_Juan_Unified_voter_guide_9-24-12.pdf\n">Voter Guide - San Juan Unified School District, Sacramento</a>\n- <a href="/Chico_%20Unified_voter_guide_9-25-12.pdf">Voter Guide - Chico Unified School District, Butte County</a>\n- <a href="/oakland_unified_voter_guide_final_9-27-12.pdf">Voter Guide - Oakland Unified School District</a>\n- <a href="/voter_guide_san_diego_unified_board_district_e_10-24-12.pdf">Voter Guide - San Diego School District - Board District E</a>\nMore guides coming soon!</p>\n', 'Non-partisan Voter Guides for November 6, 2012 School Board Elections', 'Families That Can has created easy-to-read, nonpartisan voter guides to help you learn more about the candidates running for school board in various communities across the state.\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '153-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 153, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/153-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(841, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Ayúdenos a difundir información mediante la inclusión de nuestras noticias en su boletín escolar o en su página web. Nosotros incluiremos un breve artículo en nuestra página de web todos los meses para hacer este proceso mucho más fácil para usted.</p>\n\n<h3>El 25 de Septiembre es el Día Nacional de Inscripción Electoral</h3>\n\n<p>Nuestros funcionarios electos toman decisiones importantes diariamente que afectan a nuestras escuelas y nuestros niños. Ejercer el derecho al voto es la base de nuestro sistema democrático, y un símbolo de la fortaleza de nuestras comunidades. Sea un ejemplo para sus hijos, y haga que su voz sea escuchada votando en las elecciones del 6 de noviembre.\n¿Todavía no se ha registrado?\nNuestra escuela [NOMBRE DE LA ESCUELA] está orgullosa de unirse a más de 700 grupos comunitarios de todo el país que participarán en el Día Nacional de Inscripción Electoral el 25 de septiembre. El tema de este evento nacional no-partidista es sencillo: Regístrese en septiembre, vote en noviembre.\n[Put details about how parents can participate at your school -forms in the school office, a table in front of school on Sept. 25, etc.]\nUsted puede registrarse para votar en línea o puede también recoger un formulario en la oficina electoral de su condado, bibliotecas locales, u oficinas de correo. Las elecciones son administradas por la Secretaría del Estado de California. Visite su página web en www.sos.ca.gov/elections/new-voter/spanish/ para obtener más información o para averiguar si ya está registrado.\nLos votantes pueden obtener ayuda adicional en español llamando gratis a la línea especial de la Secretaría del Estado al (800) 232-VOTA (8682)</p>\n', 'Artículo para el Septiembre: El 25 de Septiembre es el Día Nacional de Inscripción Electoral', '¡Ayúdenos correr la voz con este articulo para su boletín informativo para padres!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '152-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 152, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/152-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(842, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="Sac High Rally Protesters Dec 2011 (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/01/Rally and end of the year 062-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>Sometimes it takes years of advocacy before a school can claim victory on a challenging issue. Such was the case with Sacramento Charter High School which was just granted its first 5-year facility use agreement from the Sacramento City Unified School District Board of Education in the spring of 2012. Sac High became a charter in 2003 and has been struggling with year-to-year facility renewals from the beginning.\nAinye Long, Director of Family and Community Engagement for Families That Can, worked to mobilize parents and students last fall when a proposed facility swap would have forced Sacramento Charter High School to move to a smaller site at West Campus High School with insufficient space for athletics. She attributes the facility use agreement victory to a number of factors that have developed over the last decade.\nSacramento Charter High School has been the subject of facility-use discussions for years. Citing their declining budget, the Sacramento City Unified School District Board considered saving money by closing schools that were operating at low capacity. A West Campus/Sac High swap proposal was intended to be part of those cost-saving measures.  Like many charters, the school doesn\'t have the same high enrollment numbers as the other traditional high schools in similar sized facilities in the region. Opponents have rarely noted that Sac High was not allowed to recruit students at district middle schools until the 2011-12 school year.\nNot long after Sacramento High School was converted from a traditional high school to a charter, a small group of parents from East Sacramento joined together to form "Where\'s My High School?" WMHS leaders believed that the students in East Sacramento were left without a comprehensive high school when Sac High became a charter school. Some parents sued the district over the lack of high school options and a court agreed that a new high school would have to be built. Unfortunately, the East Sacramento area is densely populated and few locations exist that would be big enough for a new high school. Over the past eight years, many locations have been proposed by the community and school board members, but each has been challenged. To this day, an East Sacramento high school continues to be a major focus of school politics in Sacramento with a continued focus on the Sacramento Charter High Campus.\nWhen the SCUSD Board proposed the facility swap last fall, parents at both Sac High and West Campus High School fought to prevent it. It was the final straw for the community, with parents, students, teachers and board members tired of the wrestling over the Sacramento Charter High School campus for almost a decade. Many were ready to put the long-standing issue to rest. The board member who proposed the swap responded to the outcry from parents and took the proposal off the table in December 2011. By the Spring of 2012, the SCUSD board members seemed to recognize that Sac High\'s enrollment was growing and the community wanted to keep Sac High in its historic location in Oak Park, the oldest suburb of Sacramento. Parent leadership made the difference at Sac High. Families invited their board trustee to visit the school. They wrote letters. They attended board meetings. They never gave up. And in the end, they can now rest knowing that Sac High will be able to stay put for the next five years.</p>\n', '5-Year Facility Use Agreement for Sacramento Charter High School', 'Victory comes after years of work by parents\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '151-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 151, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/151-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(843, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Hay veces que una victoria para una escuela chárter tarda años en convertirse en realidad.  Tal es el caso de la escuela preparatoria Sacramento Chárter High, la cual fue otorgada un acuerdo para el uso de un edificio por un plazo de cinco años por la Junta del Distrito Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento en la primavera del 2012.  Sacramento Chárter High se convirtió en una escuela chárter en el 2003, y desde entonces, había tenido que renovar el uso de su edificio anualmente.\nAinye Long, Directora de Integración de Familias y la Comunidad de Las Familias Sí Pueden, trabajó arduamente para movilizar a padres y estudiantes el año pasado, cuando se presentó una propuesta para intercambiar los planteles escolares de Sacramento Chárter High y la escuela West Campus High, lo cual hubiera limitado el espacio disponible para actividades atléticas para estudiantes.  Ainye atribuye el acuerdo plasmado a un número de factores que han estado en desarrollo durante la última década.\nSacramento Chárter High ha estado en discusiones para el uso de su plantel por varios anos.  La Junta Escolar del Distrito Unificado de la Ciudad de Sacramento había considerado cerrar el plantel para ahorrar fondos en declive.  El intercambio de planteles entre Sacramento Chárter High y West Campus fue uno de los planes propuestos para ahorrar fondos.  Al igual que otras escuelas chárter, Sacramento Chárter High no cuenta con la misma matriculación de estudiantes que otras escuelas preparatorias de la región.  Opositores se han negado a decir que Sacramento Chárter High no contaba con el permiso para reclutar a estudiantes de escuelas secundarias hasta el año escolar del 2011-12.\nAl poco tiempo de convertirse en una escuela chárter, un grupo de padres del área de East Sacramento unieron sus fuerzas para formar el grupo "Where\'s My High School?", o "?Dónde Está Mi Preparatoria?  Estos padres aseveraron que al convertirse en una escuela chárter, Sacramento Chárter High dejó a estudiantes sin una preparatoria.  De hecho, varios presentaron una demanda contra el distrito, y una corte decidió que una nueva preparatoria sería construida.  Desafortunadamente, el área de East Sacramento está abarrotada, y existen muy pocas áreas para construir una nueva escuela preparatoria.  Durante los últimos ocho años, la comunidad y varios miembros de la junta escolar han propuesto planteles para la nueva escuela, pero ninguno se ha dado sin retos.  Actualmente, el enfoque para abrir una nueva preparatoria en East Sacramento continúa, y el plantel donde actualmente reside la escuela Sacramento Chárter High sigue siendo de gran interés.\nCuando la Junta Escolar de la Ciudad de Sacramento propuso intercambiar los planteles de Sacramento Chárter High y West Campus el año pasado, los padres de ambas escuelas lucharon para detener dicho plan.  Esta fue la última la gota que derramó el vaso de agua para la comunidad, con padres, estudiantes, maestros y miembros de la junta escolar cansados de tratar de despojar a la escuela Sacramento Chárter High de su plantel por casi una década.  Muchos estuvieron dispuestos a poner punto final a este asunto.  En diciembre del 2011, el miembro de la junta escolar que originalmente propuso el intercambio de planteles, retiró su propuesta.  Para la primavera del 2012, miembros de la Junta Escolar por fin reconocieron que la matriculación en Sacramento Chárter High estaba creciendo, y la comunidad quería que la escuela permaneciera en la histórica área de Oak Park, uno de los suburbios más antiguos de la ciudad.\nEl liderazgo de los padres realmente tuvo un impacto esencial para Sacramento Chárter High.  Varias familias invitaron a miembros de la Junta Escolar a visitar la escuela, otras escribieron cartas, y muchas más asistieron a las juntas de la directiva escolar.  Los padres jamás se dieron por vencidos.  Ahora, pueden sentirse orgullosos de que sus hijos podrán permanecer en el mismo plantel por los próximos cinco anos.</p>\n', 'Acuerdo de Cinco Años Para el Uso de Un Edificio para la Escuela Preparatoria Sacramento Chárter', 'Los esfuerzos de los padres de familia tuvieron impacto\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '150-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 150, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/150-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(844, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '<p>Families That Can recognizes that the best advocates a school can have are their parents! Parents do not have any political special interest nor do they have self-interest...the only interest a parent has is their child.  Parents are always looking for ways to get involved and support their child\'s school and we want to make sure we channel that energy and excitement to support all the wonderful things our public charter schools are doing!\nOn Thursday, September 6, 47 Parent Leaders representing different charter schools from across Los Angeles convened at Santa Monica Blvd Community Charter, a Fenton Charter School, for their Los Angeles Regional meeting.  Now you may ask yourself, what is a Parent Leader?\n"Parent Leader" isn\'t a job title; it\'s what you do. Parent Leaders are the people who have that direct contact with ALL the parents --- whether you are an Executive Director, Assistant Principal, Parent Director, Parent Coordinator,  Parent Liaison, Parent Outreach Coordinator, Dean of Students,  or a parent volunteer or head of your school\'s parent committee... titles vary across all schools, but these Parent Leaders are the gatekeepers to engaging families in school activities.\nFamilies That Can continues to empower these Parent Leaders with all the resources and tools needed to engage their families on a wide range of activities. This past meeting highlighted:\n- LAUSD Board Member Steve Zimmer\'s introduction of a resolution that wanted to limit public charter growth and parent choice\n- CIVICS - <a href="/2012/07/families-that-can-launches-the-civics-campaign.html">California Informed Voters In Charter Schools</a>\n- Families That Can\'s Partnership with <a href="http://nationalvoterregistrationday.org/">National Voter Registration Day</a> on September 25: A representative from the Los Angeles County Registrar\'s Office provided a training at the meeting to certify Parent Leaders as Deputy Registrars\n- Families That Can\'s Annual Parent Summit in San Diego, a one-day event that is part of the <a href="http://charterconference.org/2013/">California Charter Schools Association\'s annual conference</a>. This year, we will be celebrating the <a href="http://anniversary.ccsa.org">20th anniversary of California charter schools</a>!</p>\n\n<h3>Power of the Parents</h3>\n\n<p>We are amazed what Parent Leaders are capable of doing when given the knowledge and tools. On Thursday, September 8, we shared the urgency and need for the parent voice to be heard at Tuesday, September 11 school board meeting where Board Member Steve Zimmer was introducing a resolution limiting parent choice.\nWithin just a three-day turnaround, each representative went back to their school communities and hundreds of calls, emails and petitions went to all LAUSD school board members letting them know that parents will not accept limited choices for their child\'s education! Two hundred parents came to the meeting and packed the board room and they\'re ready to do it again on October 9, when this resolution comes up for a vote.\n- <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.401017803297678.94829.102530249813103&amp;type=3">See photos from the meeting on Facebook.</a>\nLeaving the board meeting definitely reassured parents of one thing - that their voice is powerful.</p>\n\n<h4>Register to vote!</h4>\n\n<p>We\'re also gearing up for National Voter Registration Day on September 25 - a great chance to let all elected officials know that charter school parents, teachers, 18 year old high school students and all community supporters will come out to vote in all upcoming elections. Families That Can has partnered with National Voter Registration Day - a nation-wide campaign to register 100,000 voters across our nation.  In Los Angeles, 50 charter schools have already committed to registering 20 new voters each! As these new partnerships and campaigns are introduced to schools, we want to make sure that they are successful and each Parent Leader feels confident and equipped to present and share out all the information with their families.</p>\n\n<h4>Save the date - December 5</h4>\n\n<p>We are eager to continue educating and empowering parents and look forward to our next Regional Charter School Parent Leader meeting on December 5 to celebrate our continued successes and prepare for upcoming LAUSD Board Member elections, Mayoral elections and City Council elections in Los Angeles.\nParents do have a voice and choice!\n<a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.400475086685283.94704.102530249813103&amp;type=1">Check out our pictures from the Sept. 8 Parent Leader meeting.</a></p>\n', '47 LA Parent Leaders Come Together to Kick Off the School Year', 'From rallying at the school board meeting to registering voters, a lot is planned for this fall!\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '149-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '2016-01-13 04:19:52', '', 149, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/149-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(845, 3, '2016-01-13 04:19:53', '2016-01-13 04:19:53', '<div class="figure embedded-image none"><img alt="extera_parent_rally_against_Zimmer_resolution_9-11-12.jpg (Entry/Page Lead Image)" src="/assets_c/2012/09/extera_parent_rally_against_Zimmer_resolution_9-11-12-cropped-proto-ftc_theme___lead.jpg" width="612" height="269" class="mt-image-none" style="" /></div>\n\n<p>On September 11, 2012, <a href="http://laschoolboard.org/sites/default/files/09-11-12RegBdCSOrderOfBusiness.pdf">LAUSD Board Member Steve Zimmer introduced a resolution to limit choices for parents</a> by not allowing the board to hear any petitions for new charter schools.\nParents packed the Los Angeles Unified School District (LAUSD) board room on Tuesday morning to share their personal stories and ask the board members to not limit choices for families.\n"Six months ago, <a href="/2012/01/join-us-feb-4.html">6,000 parents rallied asking for more school choices here in Los Angeles</a>. Have they already been forgotten?" Corri Ravare, Executive Director of Families That Can, asked Board Member Zimmer.\nIsabel Lamas from Stern MASS, a charter school in East Los Angeles that is part of the Alliance for College-Ready Public Schools, said she felt fortunate that her son was selected in the lottery, but asked board members to think of all the families whose children are on wait lists. Currently, more than 10,000 students are on wait lists for LA charter schools.\n- <a href="http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.401017803297678.94829.102530249813103&amp;type=1">See great pics from the meeting on Facebook!</a>\nFamilies That Can also presented 600 signatures from parents from across Los Angeles who couldn\'t attend the meeting in person but who signed a petition against the resolution.\n"This resolution doesn\'t serve children in Los Angeles," said Jana Harper, who chose Our Community School in Chatsworth because she wasn\'t happy with what she saw at district schools in her neighborhood. "I believe that if district schools had the independence and flexibility to allow their professionals the agility to meet the needs of the students at their school they would be competitive with public charter schools and I would celebrate it. This resolution punishes the students and their parents for wanting more for their children."\nProphet Walker, a charter school parent, told the board he attended LAUSD schools until age 16 when he was incarcerated and that he committed to education in prison and has since trained to be an engineer. He said he moved his daughter from a district school to a charter because he was frustrated with the quality and the bureaucracy.\n"Whether it\'s a charter school or a district school, I support all well-functioning academic institutions. Don\'t take away choices for students - these aren\'t throwaway kids," said Walker.\n"I\'m not here for politics - this affects our kids every day," said Raul Claros of Latino Coalition who spoke against the resolution and who told parents to spread the word to others.\n"I\'ve seen the difference," said Maria del Carmen Vasquez. Her oldest child attends an Aspire school in south LA, but her two younger children on waitlists. "I want the best for my kids - that\'s why I\'m here today."\nThe California Charter Schools Association sent live tweets throughout the meeting. <a href="http://twitter.com/lacharters">Check out @lacharters to see more quotes.</a>\nAt the meeting, Board Member Zimmer said he was listening and would present a revised resolution. The resolution will likely go up for a vote in early October.\n<a href="/2012/09/action-alert-la-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-to-stop-charter-schools-and-take-away-parent-choice.html">Take action today and tell your board member not to vote for this resolution!</a>\nSeveral media outlets also covered the story:\nAssociated Press\n- <a href="http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Parents-decry-proposed-crackdown-on-LA-charters-3855517.php">"Parents decry proposed crackdown on LA charters"</a>\n- <a href="http://www.laopinion.com/Padres_denuncian_moratoria_escuelas_charters_en_LA">Padres denuncian moratoria a escuelas charters en LA</a>\nLos Angeles Daily News\n- <a href="http://www.contracostatimes.com/california/ci_21516921/lausd-board-members-charter-school-freeze-proposal-draws">LAUSD board member\'s charter-school freeze proposal draws angry parents to meeting</a>\nLos Angeles Times\n- <a href="http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/09/charter-schools-focus-of-la-school-board-protests.html">Charter campuses focus of L.A. school-board protests</a>\n- <a href="http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/09/charter-schools-call-proposed-la-moratorium-illegal.html">Charter schools call proposed L.A. moratorium illegal</a>\nMore stories:\n- <a href="http://www.dailynews.com/ci_21493705/lausd-board-member-steve-zimmer-wants-strengthen-oversight?source=most_emailed">Los Angeles Daily News</a>\n- <a href="http://www.laopinion.com/Un_alto_a_las_charters">La Opinión</a>\n- <a href="http://abclocal.go.com/kabc/story?section=news/local/los_angeles&amp;id=8805973">KABC-TV, Channel 7</a>\n- <a href="http://www.scpr.org/blogs/education/2012/09/10/9898/does-quality-charter-schools-need-be-improved/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+893KpccSouthernCaliforniaNews+%28KPCC%3A+News%29">KPCC, 89.3 FM</a> - Reporter Adolfo Guzman-Lopez asks: "Are charter schools doing a good job?" Post your comments!\nA big thanks to all the parents who came out for the meeting, including more than 150 parents from Extera Charter School in Boyle Heights! Other schools represented included:\n- Los Angeles Leadership Academy\n- Vaughn Learning Center\n- Fenton Avenue Charter School\n- Santa Monica Boulevard Fenton Hollywood\n- Green Dot\n- Alliance College-Ready Public Schools\n- Aspire\n- Extera\n- Ocean Charter\n- Palisades Charter High School\n- Bert Corona Middle School\n- Crown Prep Academy\n- KIPP\n- Monsenor Oscar Romero\n- Vista Charter\n- Academia Moderna\n- ICEF\n- High Tech High LA\n- Our Community School\nThe board is expected to vote on the item in October.  We will keep you updated.</p>\n', 'Parents Show In Force At The LAUSD Board Room To Fight For Choice And Charters', 'Proposed resolution would impose a moratorium on new charter schools in LAUSD, limit parent choice\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '148-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-01-13 04:19:53', '2016-01-13 04:19:53', '', 148, 'http://dev.ccsafamilies.org/148-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
